00:11:26.680 --> 00:11:29.770
And he offered to pay
them if they joined up.

00:11:29.770 --> 00:11:34.570
There's a crew of Choctaw
Braves, 62 American Indian

00:11:34.570 --> 00:11:38.170
Braves who for some reason
were willing to help this guy

00:11:38.170 --> 00:11:41.980
and these people who had
been treating them badly.

00:11:41.980 --> 00:11:45.040
And Andrew Jackson
promised to pay them.

00:11:45.040 --> 00:11:48.400
And he gave this rousing
speech, where he said,

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:51.220
I know we have our
differences, but let's

00:11:51.220 --> 00:11:53.380
set aside those
differences for a second,

00:11:53.380 --> 00:11:56.140
and let's save the city
and maybe the country

00:11:56.140 --> 00:11:58.766
from these people that want
to invade our homeland.

00:11:58.766 --> 00:12:00.640
So he gave this speech,
and everyone cheered.

00:12:00.640 --> 00:12:02.056
And then he went
back to his room,

00:12:02.056 --> 00:12:05.560
and he shit himself because
of the dysentery and also

00:12:05.560 --> 00:12:09.430
because the British had this
enormous army against his 3,000

00:12:09.430 --> 00:12:12.460
misfits, none of whom had
ever fought a war before,

00:12:12.460 --> 00:12:14.630
like a real war.

00:12:14.630 --> 00:12:18.140
And so he knows that
this is a lost cause

00:12:18.140 --> 00:12:20.360
and that he's going to die
and all of these people,

00:12:20.360 --> 00:12:22.880
who he just convinced
to defend the city,

00:12:22.880 --> 00:12:24.276
are also going to die.

00:12:24.276 --> 00:12:26.900
And he knew what had happened in
these cities on the East Coast

00:12:26.900 --> 00:12:28.733
that had been sacked
and pillaged and burned

00:12:28.733 --> 00:12:30.740
and what the soldiers
did to the families

00:12:30.740 --> 00:12:34.160
and the women of these
soldiers that they'd killed.

00:12:34.160 --> 00:12:37.070
And everyone was rightly
freaked out by this.

00:12:37.070 --> 00:12:40.130
So around this time, Andrew
Jackson, with his dysentery,

00:12:40.130 --> 00:12:43.310
gets a visit from a lawyer, a
guy named Edward Livingston,

00:12:43.310 --> 00:12:45.740
who was kind of like the
Saul Goodman of those days,

00:12:45.740 --> 00:12:48.845
if anyone knows Saul Goodman.

00:12:48.845 --> 00:12:50.470
This guy shows up,
and he says, there's

00:12:50.470 --> 00:12:52.480
another group of people
who could potentially

00:12:52.480 --> 00:12:54.820
join your army.

00:12:54.820 --> 00:12:55.599
He says, who?

00:12:55.599 --> 00:12:57.640
He says, well, is Jean
Laffite and his merry band

00:12:57.640 --> 00:12:58.223
of privateers.

00:12:58.223 --> 00:13:00.580
Look at this good-looking guy.

00:13:00.580 --> 00:13:02.964
And Andrew Jackson says, no,
I don't deal with pirates.

00:13:02.964 --> 00:13:03.630
Are you kidding?

00:13:03.630 --> 00:13:04.380
They're criminals.

00:13:04.380 --> 00:13:05.590
We're not going to do this.

00:13:05.590 --> 00:13:07.840
Saul Goodman says, well,
they have a bunch of cannons.

00:13:07.840 --> 00:13:10.930
He says, actually,
yes, OK, bring them on.

00:13:10.930 --> 00:13:13.630
So Jean Laffite becomes-- this
is why this should be a movie.

00:13:13.630 --> 00:13:15.250
John Laffite becomes
a co-strategist

00:13:15.250 --> 00:13:16.125
of the defense force.

00:13:16.125 --> 00:13:18.730
So he and Andrew Jackson
become the generals

00:13:18.730 --> 00:13:20.925
of this ragtag army.

00:13:20.925 --> 00:13:23.050
So now Andrew Jackson-- if
I haven't made it clear,

00:13:23.050 --> 00:13:24.550
I don't really like this guy.

00:13:24.550 --> 00:13:27.520
He had a lot of
hate in his heart.

00:13:27.520 --> 00:13:29.080
He hated Creoles,
which is basically

00:13:29.080 --> 00:13:30.560
the Spanish and
French descendants,

00:13:30.560 --> 00:13:33.700
the immigrant community
of New Orleans.

00:13:33.700 --> 00:13:36.050
He hated pirates because
they were criminals.

00:13:36.050 --> 00:13:37.840
He hated the American Indians.

00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:39.820
He was not on the
right side of history

00:13:39.820 --> 00:13:41.440
when it came to black people.

00:13:41.440 --> 00:13:43.130
He was a slave owner.

00:13:43.130 --> 00:13:44.955
And these were all the
people in his army.

00:13:44.955 --> 00:13:47.080
But he said, I guess this
is more important for now

00:13:47.080 --> 00:13:49.990
than my personal hatred for
all these people who are not

00:13:49.990 --> 00:13:53.500
like me for whatever reason.

00:13:53.500 --> 00:13:56.440
And thus was born the most
diverse army ever assembled

00:13:56.440 --> 00:13:59.580
in the history of
the United States,

00:13:59.580 --> 00:14:02.310
under-manned, outgunned,
but very, very

00:14:02.310 --> 00:14:03.810
interesting ragtag group.

00:14:03.810 --> 00:14:08.230
So I want to sit back and
talk for a second about teams.

00:14:08.230 --> 00:14:08.820
Now, I'm here.

00:14:08.820 --> 00:14:12.330
I'm going around to
Google and other places

00:14:12.330 --> 00:14:13.890
to talk about this
book that I just

00:14:13.890 --> 00:14:16.950
wrote that everyone who's
here gets a free copy.

00:14:16.950 --> 00:14:18.907
So-- yeah, thanks.

00:14:18.907 --> 00:14:19.740
I hope you enjoy it.

00:14:19.740 --> 00:14:21.720
So, this is one of the
stories in the book.

00:14:21.720 --> 00:14:23.340
It's about teamwork.

00:14:23.340 --> 00:14:26.280
And it's about the lie we've
been told our whole lives when

00:14:26.280 --> 00:14:29.160
it comes to working together
and it comes to teamwork.

00:14:29.160 --> 00:14:31.470
And that lie is that two
heads are better than one.

00:14:31.470 --> 00:14:36.432
Turns out that two heads are
usually not better than one.

00:14:36.432 --> 00:14:37.890
And there's lots
of proof for this,

00:14:37.890 --> 00:14:41.160
but despite that,
we won planet Earth

00:14:41.160 --> 00:14:42.535
because we could band together.

00:14:42.535 --> 00:14:43.410
We were smart enough.

00:14:43.410 --> 00:14:45.349
We were equipped to collaborate.

00:14:45.349 --> 00:14:47.640
So that's how we beat all
these crazy animals that were

00:14:47.640 --> 00:14:48.984
much more ferocious than us.

00:14:48.984 --> 00:14:51.150
We were smart enough to
work together to build fire,

00:14:51.150 --> 00:14:52.650
to build civilization.

00:14:52.650 --> 00:14:55.830
And so there's a reason that
dogs look up to us and love us

00:14:55.830 --> 00:14:57.660
and they're not our master.

00:14:57.660 --> 00:14:59.250
We can make a range
of vocal sounds

00:14:59.250 --> 00:15:01.740
that they can't, so we can
communicate with each other.

00:15:01.740 --> 00:15:03.720
Even things like the
whites of our eyes

00:15:03.720 --> 00:15:05.976
are three times the size
of any other primates.

00:15:05.976 --> 00:15:07.350
So when I'm looking
at something,

00:15:07.350 --> 00:15:08.370
you can tell what
I'm looking at.

00:15:08.370 --> 00:15:10.869
It makes it easier for us to
work on things, to collaborate,

00:15:10.869 --> 00:15:12.550
even if we can't communicate.

00:15:12.550 --> 00:15:14.190
And I was really
proud of this one.

00:15:14.190 --> 00:15:17.100
This is a hipster and a gorilla.

00:15:17.100 --> 00:15:19.180
Our brains are
equipped for empathy,

00:15:19.180 --> 00:15:23.040
which means that we can mirror
the emotions of other people

00:15:23.040 --> 00:15:23.791
that we encounter.

00:15:23.791 --> 00:15:25.206
This is our brain's
way of helping

00:15:25.206 --> 00:15:26.340
us to care about someone.

00:15:26.340 --> 00:15:28.500
So when someone's in
trouble and they're

00:15:28.500 --> 00:15:30.420
running away from the
saber tooth tiger,

00:15:30.420 --> 00:15:31.584
we get adrenaline also.

00:15:31.584 --> 00:15:33.000
Our heart rate
elevates so that we

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:35.570
can run with them or
we can fight with them.

00:15:35.570 --> 00:15:38.644
And also, this empathy thing
helps us to love and care

00:15:38.644 --> 00:15:40.810
about people, so we stick
together with our families

00:15:40.810 --> 00:15:43.268
and so we stick together with
our tribes so we can survive.

00:15:43.268 --> 00:15:46.290
There are all these reasons why
humans are built to collaborate

00:15:46.290 --> 00:15:48.300
or were built to work together.

00:15:48.300 --> 00:15:51.650
But it turns out that
collaborating is hard.

00:15:51.650 --> 00:15:54.540
We say that synergy or
whatever, one plus one

00:15:54.540 --> 00:15:56.160
can equal more than two.

00:15:56.160 --> 00:15:57.767
Turns out that's
almost never true.

00:15:57.767 --> 00:15:59.850
They did these experiments
where they asked people

00:15:59.850 --> 00:16:03.190
to yell as loud as they could,
and they measured the decibels.

00:16:03.190 --> 00:16:04.800
And when you're in a room by
yourself yelling as loud as you

00:16:04.800 --> 00:16:07.050
can, you'll yell a little
bit louder than when you're

00:16:07.050 --> 00:16:09.400
in a room full of six people.

00:16:09.400 --> 00:16:10.937
And that was sort of strange.

00:16:10.937 --> 00:16:12.520
They did these other
experiments where

00:16:12.520 --> 00:16:14.194
they had people pull on a rope.

00:16:14.194 --> 00:16:16.360
And it turns out that when
you're doing a tug of war

00:16:16.360 --> 00:16:18.940
with a group of people,
you exert less force

00:16:18.940 --> 00:16:21.360
on the rope, a little bit,
than you do by yourself.

00:16:21.360 --> 00:16:23.110
Even if you're like
this kid and you think

00:16:23.110 --> 00:16:25.619
you're pulling your hardest.

00:16:25.619 --> 00:16:27.910
And some people will say,
well, this is social loafing.

00:16:27.910 --> 00:16:30.799
Someone on the tug-of-war rope
or someone in the yelling room

00:16:30.799 --> 00:16:32.590
is slacking off because
of the group, which

00:16:32.590 --> 00:16:34.240
happens, definitely happens.

00:16:34.240 --> 00:16:35.950
Some of this might
be coordination.

00:16:35.950 --> 00:16:38.330
You have a lot of people,
coordinating is hard.

00:16:38.330 --> 00:16:41.650
The only cliche more
common I think in business

00:16:41.650 --> 00:16:44.350
than synergy is how long it
takes to turn a battleship,

00:16:44.350 --> 00:16:44.920
right?

00:16:44.920 --> 00:16:47.545
You have a lot of people, a big
organization is hard to change.

00:16:47.545 --> 00:16:48.460
It's slow.

00:16:48.460 --> 00:16:49.960
But there's other
stuff that happens

00:16:49.960 --> 00:16:53.630
that's psychological when humans
come together to work together.

00:16:53.630 --> 00:16:56.110
This is my favorite
series of stock photos.

00:16:56.110 --> 00:16:59.470
I like to call it "White Guy
Leads Brainstorm Session."

00:16:59.470 --> 00:17:02.170
So, it turns out that
over and over again,

00:17:02.170 --> 00:17:04.569
when researchers put people
in rooms or around a table

00:17:04.569 --> 00:17:08.500
to brainstorm ideas, a
group of the same people,

00:17:08.500 --> 00:17:10.740
just as smart or the
same actual people,

00:17:10.740 --> 00:17:13.619
will come up with fewer ideas
and fewer good ideas together

00:17:13.619 --> 00:17:15.960
in the same room than
they will on their own

00:17:15.960 --> 00:17:18.550
and then if they just add
up their lists of ideas.

00:17:18.550 --> 00:17:21.147
And they've shown this so often
that one famous psychologist

00:17:21.147 --> 00:17:23.730
said that "business people must
be insane to use brainstorming

00:17:23.730 --> 00:17:24.869
exercises."

00:17:24.869 --> 00:17:27.089
My favorite, one
of their colleagues

00:17:27.089 --> 00:17:28.890
said that something
like, as surely

00:17:28.890 --> 00:17:31.560
as cigarettes lead
to lung cancer,

00:17:31.560 --> 00:17:35.370
brainstorming in groups leads
to not as good of ideas.

00:17:35.370 --> 00:17:36.660
So this is sort of depressing.

00:17:36.660 --> 00:17:38.280
And there's lots
of reasons for it,

00:17:38.280 --> 00:17:41.250
our need to fit into the group.

00:17:41.250 --> 00:17:43.530
Sometimes it's unsafe to
express certain ideas that

00:17:43.530 --> 00:17:45.180
might come to us
when we're alone,

00:17:45.180 --> 00:17:46.404
when there's a group dynamic.

00:17:46.404 --> 00:17:48.570
Whatever it is, we see this
phenomenon over and over

00:17:48.570 --> 00:17:51.090
and over again that when
we put our heads together,

00:17:51.090 --> 00:17:54.149
we usually don't add up to more.

00:17:54.149 --> 00:17:56.190
Maybe we add up to just
as much, but we certainly

00:17:56.190 --> 00:17:57.420
don't add up to more.

00:17:57.420 --> 00:17:58.200
And then there's
the other thing that

00:17:58.200 --> 00:17:59.850
happens when groups
come together,

00:17:59.850 --> 00:18:00.900
is we have differences.

00:18:00.900 --> 00:18:02.820
So we get in each other's faces.

00:18:02.820 --> 00:18:06.834
Our different opinions cause
us to fight, to have conflict.

00:18:06.834 --> 00:18:08.250
Sometimes we even
try to destroy--

00:18:08.250 --> 00:18:10.833
this is my second "It's Always
Sunny" slide, for anyone that's

00:18:10.833 --> 00:18:12.180
a fan of the show.

00:18:12.180 --> 00:18:16.270
Sometimes we try to destroy each
other when we come together.

00:18:16.270 --> 00:18:20.430
But the reality is that we
can't build anything big

00:18:20.430 --> 00:18:22.307
without more than one person.

00:18:22.307 --> 00:18:23.890
You can't make Google
with one person.

00:18:23.890 --> 00:18:24.930
That's why we're
all here, right?

00:18:24.930 --> 00:18:26.726
You can't build a
building by yourself.

00:18:26.726 --> 00:18:28.350
You can do a heart
surgery by yourself.

00:18:28.350 --> 00:18:30.016
You can't even clean
the stadium in time

00:18:30.016 --> 00:18:33.220
for the next game
with one person.

00:18:33.220 --> 00:18:35.910
So we endure this
loss of productivity

00:18:35.910 --> 00:18:37.410
that comes with group work.

00:18:37.410 --> 00:18:39.870
We endure these squabbles
and these fights

00:18:39.870 --> 00:18:42.600
and the jerks that
try and foil us.

00:18:42.600 --> 00:18:44.840
And then we put up walls
against each other.

00:18:44.840 --> 00:18:46.465
We say, we don't want
to listen to you.

00:18:46.465 --> 00:18:49.190
We try and put our rivals
and our critics on the floor.

00:18:49.190 --> 00:18:52.000
And we beat our
plowshares into swords,

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:55.860
and we turn nuclear energy,
this wonderful potential power,

00:18:55.860 --> 00:18:58.890
into a bomb.

00:18:58.890 --> 00:19:02.220
And the very same thing
leads to all of this.

00:19:02.220 --> 00:19:05.380
It's the differences
we have between us.

00:19:05.380 --> 00:19:09.850
And yet, some teams actually
do manage to feel magical.

00:19:09.850 --> 00:19:12.070
And maybe some of you have
felt this way when you've

00:19:12.070 --> 00:19:14.590
worked together in groups or
you've been part of something

00:19:14.590 --> 00:19:17.567
where it feels like
whatever you're up to,

00:19:17.567 --> 00:19:18.650
you can do the impossible.

00:19:18.650 --> 00:19:20.110
You feel infinite.

00:19:20.110 --> 00:19:22.360
And sometimes the team
that isn't supposed to win

00:19:22.360 --> 00:19:25.082
overcomes the odds,
and they do win.

00:19:25.082 --> 00:19:27.040
Anyone that's had a family
knows that sometimes

00:19:27.040 --> 00:19:29.410
with human beings, one plus
one can equal more than two,

00:19:29.410 --> 00:19:30.830
literally.

00:19:30.830 --> 00:19:33.520
And so this is how
every great movement,

00:19:33.520 --> 00:19:36.100
every great breakthrough
in history of society

00:19:36.100 --> 00:19:39.010
has come about, is when
different humans came together,

00:19:39.010 --> 00:19:40.100
and they worked together.

00:19:40.100 --> 00:19:42.870
They linked arms, and
they overcame the odds.

00:19:42.870 --> 00:19:44.630
And this is important,
because this

00:19:44.630 --> 00:19:46.660
what we're trying to do,
not just in our work,

00:19:46.660 --> 00:19:49.270
but in general, as we're
part of the team of humans

00:19:49.270 --> 00:19:51.070
that owns this planet now.

00:19:51.070 --> 00:19:53.470
But the reality is, when
humans come together,

00:19:53.470 --> 00:19:56.860
we either break down
or we break through.

00:19:56.860 --> 00:19:58.870
And the thing that leads
to both of those things

00:19:58.870 --> 00:19:59.900
is kind of the same thing.

00:19:59.900 --> 00:20:02.191
It's the subtle interactions
between our different ways

00:20:02.191 --> 00:20:02.917
of thinking.

00:20:02.917 --> 00:20:04.750
So this is the thing
that I've been obsessed

00:20:04.750 --> 00:20:07.870
with over the last
many years, as someone

00:20:07.870 --> 00:20:11.350
who is covering innovation
for magazines like "Wired"

00:20:11.350 --> 00:20:14.662
and then starting my own company
and realizing that we needed

00:20:14.662 --> 00:20:16.870
to work together better if
we wanted to break through

00:20:16.870 --> 00:20:18.590
instead of breaking down.

00:20:18.590 --> 00:20:20.740
And it turns out
that there is math

00:20:20.740 --> 00:20:23.410
behind this paradox of
synergy, or the lack

00:20:23.410 --> 00:20:25.480
thereof, that those
groups that do

00:20:25.480 --> 00:20:27.484
feel infinite that
do add up to more,

00:20:27.484 --> 00:20:28.900
they have something
going for them

00:20:28.900 --> 00:20:31.780
that has actually been proven
out in mathematical models.

00:20:31.780 --> 00:20:34.330
And so to explain this--
and I promise I'll get back

00:20:34.330 --> 00:20:36.730
to the pirate story--

00:20:36.730 --> 00:20:39.310
join me at a dinner
party where you've

00:20:39.310 --> 00:20:42.040
baked this delicious
chocolate cake for dessert

00:20:42.040 --> 00:20:44.380
for your eight best friends.

00:20:44.380 --> 00:20:47.240
And it's a delicious
round cake, and you

00:20:47.240 --> 00:20:49.960
need to cut it into
eight equal slices.

00:20:49.960 --> 00:20:52.180
So, everyone kind of knows
how to do this, right?

00:20:52.180 --> 00:20:56.230
But pretend for whatever
reason the knife you're using

00:20:56.230 --> 00:20:57.040
is enchanted.

00:20:57.040 --> 00:20:59.380
It's a magic party
for some reason.

00:20:59.380 --> 00:21:02.260
And it's going to disappear
after you make three cuts.

00:21:02.260 --> 00:21:05.260
So how do you make eight
slices of cake with three cuts?

00:21:05.260 --> 00:21:07.780
Now, some people will instantly
know the answer to this,

00:21:07.780 --> 00:21:10.870
but most people, and me
included, will do this.

00:21:10.870 --> 00:21:13.660
They'll take the cake by cutting
it in half like a pizza, cut

00:21:13.660 --> 00:21:14.727
in half again.

00:21:14.727 --> 00:21:16.810
And then when you realize
that you're out of cuts,

00:21:16.810 --> 00:21:19.840
your third cut, if you had just
one more, you could make eight.

00:21:19.840 --> 00:21:22.010
Third and final cut only
makes six slices of cake,

00:21:22.010 --> 00:21:25.850
and two of your friends know you
love them more than the others.

00:21:25.850 --> 00:21:27.647
So how do you solve this puzzle?

00:21:27.647 --> 00:21:29.980
How do you make three cuts
to make eight slices of cake?

00:21:29.980 --> 00:21:30.850
Someone--

00:21:30.850 --> 00:21:32.949
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:21:32.949 --> 00:21:33.740
SHANE SNOW: The z--

00:21:33.740 --> 00:21:34.240
yeah.

00:21:34.240 --> 00:21:34.780
Yep.

00:21:34.780 --> 00:21:36.530
So, some people will
immediately see this.

00:21:36.530 --> 00:21:39.155
Some people say, well, you could
do some curvy S calculus cuts.

00:21:39.155 --> 00:21:41.321
Can't do that, because your
friends need to know you

00:21:41.321 --> 00:21:42.330
love them equally.

00:21:42.330 --> 00:21:44.986
So what you do is you cut it
in half, cut it in half again,

00:21:44.986 --> 00:21:46.610
and then you literally
turn the problem

00:21:46.610 --> 00:21:49.395
on its side, the z-axis, and
you cut it all the way through.

00:21:49.395 --> 00:21:51.950
Now, some of your friends
get less frosting this way,

00:21:51.950 --> 00:21:53.991
but if we pretend there's
frosting in the middle,

00:21:53.991 --> 00:21:56.270
then maybe they all
know you love them.

00:21:56.270 --> 00:21:59.515
I like to say that if you
give this puzzle to a kid,

00:21:59.515 --> 00:22:01.640
they might actually have
an easier time getting it,

00:22:01.640 --> 00:22:03.306
because they're this
high off the ground

00:22:03.306 --> 00:22:06.260
and they look at the
cake from this level.

00:22:06.260 --> 00:22:08.270
But all it takes is
turning the problem around

00:22:08.270 --> 00:22:10.790
to see that there's
a solution to it that

00:22:10.790 --> 00:22:12.420
makes eight slices of cake.

00:22:12.420 --> 00:22:14.750
So, this is a
literal, fun example

00:22:14.750 --> 00:22:17.020
of what I call one
half of our mental tool

00:22:17.020 --> 00:22:18.817
kit, which is perspective.

00:22:18.817 --> 00:22:20.650
So when psychologists
talk about perspective

00:22:20.650 --> 00:22:23.210
and neuroscientists, they
say that it is the way

00:22:23.210 --> 00:22:25.490
that we encode what we
encounter in the world

00:22:25.490 --> 00:22:28.060
into our own internal language.

00:22:28.060 --> 00:22:30.040
So inside of our brains,
we process things,

00:22:30.040 --> 00:22:32.248
and we internalize them in
our own little programming

00:22:32.248 --> 00:22:32.800
language.

00:22:32.800 --> 00:22:34.965
And everyone's is a
little bit different,

00:22:34.965 --> 00:22:36.340
but there are lots
of things that

00:22:36.340 --> 00:22:38.860
can help us to form similar
perspectives or not,

00:22:38.860 --> 00:22:42.250
so everything from
where you grew up,

00:22:42.250 --> 00:22:44.600
generation you grew
up in, who you are,

00:22:44.600 --> 00:22:47.050
how you identify,
to the stories,

00:22:47.050 --> 00:22:48.980
the experiences you've
had in your life.

00:22:48.980 --> 00:22:51.010
So, if we're walking
down the street

00:22:51.010 --> 00:22:55.300
and there's a building on fire,
if you've been in a burning

00:22:55.300 --> 00:22:57.670
building before, you're going
to encode that situation

00:22:57.670 --> 00:22:59.500
in a different
perspective then if you're

00:22:59.500 --> 00:23:02.800
a firefighter than me, who
I've never had anything

00:23:02.800 --> 00:23:03.550
to do with fire.

00:23:03.550 --> 00:23:05.560
So the things we've been
through in our lives

00:23:05.560 --> 00:23:08.320
help us form perspective.

00:23:08.320 --> 00:23:11.050
If I would hazard a guess
based on you saying the z-axis,

00:23:11.050 --> 00:23:14.305
probably something in your life
or training or whatever it is

00:23:14.305 --> 00:23:18.909
leads you to have that 3D
graph mentality in your head.

00:23:18.909 --> 00:23:19.450
I don't know.

00:23:19.450 --> 00:23:21.199
Are you an engineer
or mathematician or--?

00:23:21.199 --> 00:23:23.170
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:23:23.170 --> 00:23:24.610
SHANE SNOW: 3D CAD systems.

00:23:24.610 --> 00:23:25.870
Yeah, exactly.

00:23:25.870 --> 00:23:29.140
So you are used to looking
at physical problems

00:23:29.140 --> 00:23:31.522
literally from
three-dimensional perspectives.

00:23:31.522 --> 00:23:33.230
So there's lots of
things that form this.

00:23:33.230 --> 00:23:34.390
We all kind of know this.

00:23:34.390 --> 00:23:37.000
There's a second half
of our mental toolkit

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:39.970
that we'll go back to our party
and we'll talk about this.

00:23:39.970 --> 00:23:43.330
So, you have three
glasses of milk

00:23:43.330 --> 00:23:45.905
and three empty glasses
at this cake party.

00:23:45.905 --> 00:23:47.530
And the challenge,
for whatever reason,

00:23:47.530 --> 00:23:50.800
the puzzle is you need to
alternate these glasses so they

00:23:50.800 --> 00:23:52.510
go full, empty,
full, empty, full,

00:23:52.510 --> 00:23:56.140
empty so no two full glasses
are next to each other.

00:23:56.140 --> 00:23:58.570
Now, how do you do this
if, for whatever reason,

00:23:58.570 --> 00:24:02.622
again, magic, you can
only move one glass?

00:24:02.622 --> 00:24:05.080
And once again, some people
will instantly know the answer,

00:24:05.080 --> 00:24:06.496
and some people
will take a while.

00:24:06.496 --> 00:24:09.190
And if you're like me,
you think it's impossible.

00:24:09.190 --> 00:24:11.449
So, most people will
take the second glass,

00:24:11.449 --> 00:24:13.490
and they'll move it in
between these two glasses.

00:24:13.490 --> 00:24:14.800
And then you realize that
you had one more move,

00:24:14.800 --> 00:24:15.370
you could do this.

00:24:15.370 --> 00:24:17.650
So, most people will take
this and then move it here.

00:24:17.650 --> 00:24:19.880
There's still two glasses
next to each other.

00:24:19.880 --> 00:24:21.080
Does anyone have the answer?

00:24:21.080 --> 00:24:23.470
Anyone know how you
can move one glass

00:24:23.470 --> 00:24:25.576
and alternate them full, empty?

00:24:25.576 --> 00:24:26.700
Were you raising your hand?

00:24:26.700 --> 00:24:28.908
No?

00:24:28.908 --> 00:24:31.624
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:24:31.624 --> 00:24:33.540
SHANE SNOW: Yes, so you
take the second glass,

00:24:33.540 --> 00:24:35.145
and you pour it into
the second-to-last one,

00:24:35.145 --> 00:24:36.186
and then you put it down.

00:24:36.186 --> 00:24:37.754
You've only moved one glass.

00:24:37.754 --> 00:24:39.420
Now, I want to ask
people this question,

00:24:39.420 --> 00:24:41.520
and they don't get
it if I tell them,

00:24:41.520 --> 00:24:43.450
pretend that you just
got home from your job,

00:24:43.450 --> 00:24:45.469
your day job as a chemist.

00:24:45.469 --> 00:24:47.010
Most people will
then get the answer,

00:24:47.010 --> 00:24:48.780
because you realize
a chemist, their job

00:24:48.780 --> 00:24:50.640
is to pour things in and
out of beakers, I think.

00:24:50.640 --> 00:24:52.770
That's what we think of
when we think of a chemist.

00:24:52.770 --> 00:24:54.780
But this is called-- the
solution to this puzzle

00:24:54.780 --> 00:24:57.380
is basically heuristics.

00:24:57.380 --> 00:25:00.660
Heuristics are strategies,
approaches to solving

00:25:00.660 --> 00:25:02.320
a problem, or rules of thumb.

00:25:02.320 --> 00:25:04.320
There's lots of different
ways we refer to them.

00:25:04.320 --> 00:25:06.900
But heuristics sometimes
are very connected

00:25:06.900 --> 00:25:07.740
to our perspectives.

00:25:07.740 --> 00:25:10.800
How we see something leads
us to develop a different way

00:25:10.800 --> 00:25:13.140
to solve a problem or
approach a problem.

00:25:13.140 --> 00:25:14.809
But often they're very detached.

00:25:14.809 --> 00:25:17.100
So heuristics come from all
sorts of things, how you've

00:25:17.100 --> 00:25:19.320
had to navigate life,
but also very much

00:25:19.320 --> 00:25:22.022
comes down to your education
and, again, the experiences

00:25:22.022 --> 00:25:23.730
that you've had, what
you've been invited

00:25:23.730 --> 00:25:25.500
to do, what you've
been excluded from,

00:25:25.500 --> 00:25:27.624
how you have to go
navigate the world.

00:25:27.624 --> 00:25:29.790
My favorite example of this
that I wrote in the book

00:25:29.790 --> 00:25:33.300
is when I talk about police
work, detective work.

00:25:33.300 --> 00:25:37.320
Interviewed basically every
highest-ranking female officer

00:25:37.320 --> 00:25:42.180
in law enforcement, so ATF, FBI,
bunch of homicide detectives.

00:25:42.180 --> 00:25:44.730
And all of them
universally told me

00:25:44.730 --> 00:25:46.620
something really
interesting, which

00:25:46.620 --> 00:25:48.930
was-- because I had
the question of, why

00:25:48.930 --> 00:25:52.410
are there so few women
in law enforcement

00:25:52.410 --> 00:25:55.740
when statistics show that
women shoot people wrongfully

00:25:55.740 --> 00:25:58.490
six times less than men
do in law enforcement?

00:25:58.490 --> 00:26:00.000
So that's an
interesting question.

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:02.470
You can read about it in the
first chapter of the book.

00:26:02.470 --> 00:26:04.680
But most of the
women I interviewed

00:26:04.680 --> 00:26:08.310
said, well, if you grow up and
realize around middle school

00:26:08.310 --> 00:26:10.560
that you have less upper-body
strength than the boys

00:26:10.560 --> 00:26:13.830
in your class, then your
solution to physical problems

00:26:13.830 --> 00:26:16.440
often is not the same
thing that they do.

00:26:16.440 --> 00:26:17.851
So you encounter a locked door.

00:26:17.851 --> 00:26:19.350
Instead of immediately
trying to see

00:26:19.350 --> 00:26:21.900
if you can knock it
down or kick it open,

00:26:21.900 --> 00:26:25.890
you actually resort
to potentially trying

00:26:25.890 --> 00:26:27.290
to compromise
whoever has the key

00:26:27.290 --> 00:26:29.850
or finding some way to negotiate
the opening of the door.

00:26:29.850 --> 00:26:31.590
And this is not universal.

00:26:31.590 --> 00:26:34.414
But in general, if you
grow up a certain way,

00:26:34.414 --> 00:26:37.080
then you develop different kinds
of strategies for certain types

00:26:37.080 --> 00:26:38.944
of situations.

00:26:38.944 --> 00:26:40.110
And that's just one example.

00:26:40.110 --> 00:26:41.520
But whatever it is
you've been through

00:26:41.520 --> 00:26:43.770
can be relevant to looking at
a problem in a different way

00:26:43.770 --> 00:26:45.145
or can be relevant
to approaching

00:26:45.145 --> 00:26:46.720
a problem in a different way.

00:26:46.720 --> 00:26:48.136
So the way this
all comes together

00:26:48.136 --> 00:26:50.650
with the math of
synergy is like this.

00:26:50.650 --> 00:26:52.830
You have this cartoon
mountain range,

00:26:52.830 --> 00:26:56.430
which represents any problem
you're ever working on in life.

00:26:56.430 --> 00:26:58.619
It can be represented
by a range of solutions.

00:26:58.619 --> 00:27:00.910
So if we pretend that every
peak on this mountain range

00:27:00.910 --> 00:27:02.720
represents a different
quality of solution--

00:27:02.720 --> 00:27:04.636
the taller the peak, the
better the solution--

00:27:04.636 --> 00:27:06.676
we can say any problem
you encounter in life

00:27:06.676 --> 00:27:07.800
can be represented by this.

00:27:07.800 --> 00:27:10.946
There's good solutions,
there's less good solutions.

00:27:10.946 --> 00:27:12.570
And whenever we're
looking at a problem

00:27:12.570 --> 00:27:13.470
or we're approaching
something, it's

00:27:13.470 --> 00:27:15.930
like we're hiking around this
mountain range in the fog,

00:27:15.930 --> 00:27:18.340
and you get to the top of a
peak, and you have to decide,

00:27:18.340 --> 00:27:20.298
do we go downhill and
try and find another one,

00:27:20.298 --> 00:27:21.760
or have we found a good one?

00:27:21.760 --> 00:27:23.160
How do we navigate this?

00:27:23.160 --> 00:27:25.099
So your perspective
is basically where you

00:27:25.099 --> 00:27:26.390
get dropped on the mount range.

00:27:26.390 --> 00:27:28.000
So let's pretend this is me.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:29.790
I get dropped off here.

00:27:29.790 --> 00:27:30.780
You go uphill at first.

00:27:30.780 --> 00:27:33.000
You look for the closest
solution to the problem.

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:36.850
And then my heuristic is
basically what I do next.

00:27:36.850 --> 00:27:38.130
So I grew up in Idaho.

00:27:38.130 --> 00:27:41.160
Let's pretend that in Idaho
in mountain-climbing school,

00:27:41.160 --> 00:27:42.752
they say the rule
of thumb is when

00:27:42.752 --> 00:27:45.210
you get to the top of the peak,
you go down the other side,

00:27:45.210 --> 00:27:47.040
and you walk 50 paces.

00:27:47.040 --> 00:27:49.650
And if it starts going uphill
by then, then you keep going.

00:27:49.650 --> 00:27:50.880
And if it doesn't,
then you retreat back

00:27:50.880 --> 00:27:51.600
to the mountain peak you're on.

00:27:51.600 --> 00:27:53.520
You're probably in
a pretty good spot.

00:27:53.520 --> 00:27:56.220
So my heuristic, basically
I go down 50 paces.

00:27:56.220 --> 00:27:58.060
I say, nope, it's still fog.

00:27:58.060 --> 00:28:00.840
It's going downhill,
probably have a good solution

00:28:00.840 --> 00:28:01.507
to this problem.

00:28:01.507 --> 00:28:03.923
So you can see I haven't ended
up on a very good solution,

00:28:03.923 --> 00:28:06.180
but it is a solution to
whatever the problem is.

00:28:06.180 --> 00:28:09.559
Now, say someone on my team
has a similar perspective.

00:28:09.559 --> 00:28:11.100
She gets dropped
off on the mountain.

00:28:11.100 --> 00:28:12.684
She's looking at it
from the same way.

00:28:12.684 --> 00:28:14.266
We've worked together
for a long time,

00:28:14.266 --> 00:28:16.710
whatever the reason for us
having a similar perspective.

00:28:16.710 --> 00:28:18.131
But she has a
different heuristic.

00:28:18.131 --> 00:28:20.130
She went to a different
mountain-climbing school

00:28:20.130 --> 00:28:20.629
than me.

00:28:20.629 --> 00:28:23.399
And so she goes
uphill, and heuristic

00:28:23.399 --> 00:28:25.190
is you get to the top
of the mountain peak,

00:28:25.190 --> 00:28:27.023
go over to the other
side, and you hike down

00:28:27.023 --> 00:28:29.730
until you get to the trough
between two mountains.

00:28:29.730 --> 00:28:32.580
And then you look and you say,
which way goes up steeper?

00:28:32.580 --> 00:28:33.840
Whatever way that is, you go.

00:28:33.840 --> 00:28:35.620
So she gets down here.

00:28:35.620 --> 00:28:36.870
She says, this way is steeper.

00:28:36.870 --> 00:28:37.950
She goes up here.

00:28:37.950 --> 00:28:40.290
She gets to here, says,
nope, it's not as steep.

00:28:40.290 --> 00:28:42.610
I found a better
solution to the problem.

00:28:42.610 --> 00:28:44.944
Now, how teamwork usually
works is if we're a good team,

00:28:44.944 --> 00:28:47.026
then she'll yell down, and
she'll say, hey, Shane,

00:28:47.026 --> 00:28:48.870
I found a better
solution to the problem.

00:28:48.870 --> 00:28:50.110
Yay, teamwork.

00:28:50.110 --> 00:28:51.480
We got somewhere.

00:28:51.480 --> 00:28:54.030
And this is where that
two heads are better

00:28:54.030 --> 00:28:56.550
than one thing comes into play.

00:28:56.550 --> 00:28:58.465
It turns out that
this group is only

00:28:58.465 --> 00:29:00.840
going to be as smart as the
smartest person in this group

00:29:00.840 --> 00:29:02.360
or the person who
has the right tool

00:29:02.360 --> 00:29:04.665
kit, right combination of
perspective in heuristic

00:29:04.665 --> 00:29:05.665
to get the furthest.

00:29:05.665 --> 00:29:07.290
And then the rest of
the group follows.

00:29:07.290 --> 00:29:10.560
And this is where we get
things like best practices.

00:29:10.560 --> 00:29:12.360
So we find a solution
to whatever problem

00:29:12.360 --> 00:29:13.414
it is that's good.

00:29:13.414 --> 00:29:14.580
And then we say, this is it.

00:29:14.580 --> 00:29:15.760
This is the way to do it.

00:29:15.760 --> 00:29:17.400
We all start with
this perspective,

00:29:17.400 --> 00:29:19.650
and we all solve it this way.

00:29:19.650 --> 00:29:21.960
But little do we know,
there is a better solution

00:29:21.960 --> 00:29:23.940
out there that we
just can't get to.

00:29:23.940 --> 00:29:27.120
And in fact, our success leads
to this cognitive entrenchment,

00:29:27.120 --> 00:29:30.240
where we can't actually
see anything else.

00:29:30.240 --> 00:29:32.894
And maybe sometimes an
earthquake has happened.

00:29:32.894 --> 00:29:33.810
The world has changed.

00:29:33.810 --> 00:29:35.510
There's a new mountain
that we don't see.

00:29:35.510 --> 00:29:37.385
And disruption is
basically when someone else

00:29:37.385 --> 00:29:40.460
finds that and leaves us on
this lower mountain peak.

00:29:40.460 --> 00:29:42.655
So, how the math
of synergy works

00:29:42.655 --> 00:29:44.300
is someone with a
different perspective

00:29:44.300 --> 00:29:45.800
is like someone who
gets dropped off

00:29:45.800 --> 00:29:47.550
on a different part
of the mountain range.

00:29:47.550 --> 00:29:49.796
And then this dude
with the hat, however

00:29:49.796 --> 00:29:51.795
he navigates with his
perspective and heuristic,

00:29:51.795 --> 00:29:53.874
he's going to end up somewhere.

00:29:53.874 --> 00:29:55.790
And literally in this
cartoon, this works out.

00:29:55.790 --> 00:29:59.800
If we say, well, what if
we tried my way or her way,

00:29:59.800 --> 00:30:02.690
the go down to the steep
part, from his point of view?

00:30:02.690 --> 00:30:05.190
And if you do that, you actually
end up going the steep way.

00:30:05.190 --> 00:30:06.648
And this is how
the whole group can

00:30:06.648 --> 00:30:09.110
become smarter than any
one person in the group,

00:30:09.110 --> 00:30:10.610
is when you combine
the perspectives

00:30:10.610 --> 00:30:11.420
and the heuristics.

00:30:11.420 --> 00:30:13.990
So this is what's called
cognitive diversity

00:30:13.990 --> 00:30:15.890
in psychology.

00:30:15.890 --> 00:30:19.310
Basically, the more different
perspectives and heuristics

00:30:19.310 --> 00:30:20.960
we have for a
problem, the more we

00:30:20.960 --> 00:30:23.120
can turn it around and
potentially find solutions

00:30:23.120 --> 00:30:24.530
that are better than any group.

00:30:24.530 --> 00:30:26.790
So two heads are
only better than one

00:30:26.790 --> 00:30:30.240
if they have a diverse
combination of those things.

00:30:30.240 --> 00:30:32.960
So where does cognitive
diversity come from?

00:30:32.960 --> 00:30:35.655
Really, this cognitive mosaic
that we see the world through

00:30:35.655 --> 00:30:38.030
and we navigate the world
through, it's our perspectives.

00:30:38.030 --> 00:30:38.863
It's our heuristics.

00:30:38.863 --> 00:30:41.480
It's something I call how
you roll, how we attack

00:30:41.480 --> 00:30:43.190
the mountain, how we operate.

00:30:43.190 --> 00:30:46.060
And this is all formed
by our life experiences,

00:30:46.060 --> 00:30:48.710
the day-to-day
experiences we've had,

00:30:48.710 --> 00:30:52.070
our education, our work,
places we've been and lived,

00:30:52.070 --> 00:30:54.860
opportunities and exclusions
we've had, people we've met,

00:30:54.860 --> 00:30:56.568
people who have helped
us on our journey.

00:30:56.568 --> 00:30:58.115
This forms all of these things.

00:30:58.115 --> 00:31:00.240
And this is where we start
to get into work culture

00:31:00.240 --> 00:31:01.024
territory.

00:31:01.024 --> 00:31:02.440
What forms these
life experiences?

00:31:02.440 --> 00:31:05.670
Well, these are very much part
of our internal and external

00:31:05.670 --> 00:31:08.910
attributes, who we are, age,
gender, race, orientation,

00:31:08.910 --> 00:31:13.049
habits, parental status, you
grew up with parents or not.

00:31:13.049 --> 00:31:15.090
All these things form our
life experiences, which

00:31:15.090 --> 00:31:17.190
then form our cognitive mosaic.

00:31:17.190 --> 00:31:19.042
Now, all of these
things are not going

00:31:19.042 --> 00:31:21.000
to be relevant to every
problem, every mountain

00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:22.500
range we work on.

00:31:22.500 --> 00:31:24.840
But many of them
are, and we tend

00:31:24.840 --> 00:31:27.491
to underestimate how these
different kinds of things

00:31:27.491 --> 00:31:29.740
lead us to have different
ways of looking at problems.

00:31:29.740 --> 00:31:32.530
So like I said, two heads
are only better than one

00:31:32.530 --> 00:31:34.880
if those heads see things
differently enough.

00:31:34.880 --> 00:31:36.510
And in the book, I
get deeper into kind

00:31:36.510 --> 00:31:40.470
of these mathematical models
for how this works but mostly

00:31:40.470 --> 00:31:43.560
through cartoon form.

00:31:43.560 --> 00:31:48.100
But it only works if you
actually combine these things.

00:31:48.100 --> 00:31:50.700
So, if you have people
with all this potential

00:31:50.700 --> 00:31:52.824
to find the solution
of the problem

00:31:52.824 --> 00:31:54.240
but you don't
listen to the person

00:31:54.240 --> 00:31:55.830
with the other perspective on
the other side of the mountain

00:31:55.830 --> 00:31:57.870
range, you say, la, la,
la, we're not listening,

00:31:57.870 --> 00:31:59.670
then you're not
going to get there.

00:31:59.670 --> 00:32:01.740
Or even worse, if
this person doesn't

00:32:01.740 --> 00:32:05.010
feel like it's safe enough to
speak up about what they see

00:32:05.010 --> 00:32:08.170
and how they see the
problem, or if they say,

00:32:08.170 --> 00:32:10.800
hey we don't care what you say,
you need to fit the culture,

00:32:10.800 --> 00:32:12.540
so get down off the mountain,
come over to this side

00:32:12.540 --> 00:32:13.390
and climb up here.

00:32:13.390 --> 00:32:14.830
This is the way we do things.

00:32:14.830 --> 00:32:18.740
That's the death of problem
solving and innovation.

00:32:18.740 --> 00:32:21.680
But this basically explains
kind of every problem

00:32:21.680 --> 00:32:23.490
in corporate America.

00:32:23.490 --> 00:32:25.670
So for any of this to
work, you don't just

00:32:25.670 --> 00:32:27.740
need the different
cognitive mosaics.

00:32:27.740 --> 00:32:29.710
You need cognitive
friction also,

00:32:29.710 --> 00:32:32.120
which, if I can go
on another diversion,

00:32:32.120 --> 00:32:33.620
this is not
coincidentally how we

00:32:33.620 --> 00:32:36.290
got hip-hop, which is the thing
that Eric and I have bonded

00:32:36.290 --> 00:32:37.070
over.

00:32:37.070 --> 00:32:39.250
So, I moved to New York.

00:32:39.250 --> 00:32:40.310
I grew up in Idaho.

00:32:40.310 --> 00:32:43.820
I did not know why Notorious
BIG was so notorious.

00:32:43.820 --> 00:32:45.710
I did not know how
to pronounce RZA.

00:32:45.710 --> 00:32:48.020
I thought it was R,
Z, A. I could quote

00:32:48.020 --> 00:32:50.900
every lyric to the song "Country
Girl, (Shake It For Me)"

00:32:50.900 --> 00:32:52.100
and "Fishing in the Dark."

00:32:52.100 --> 00:32:53.000
So I knew nothing about hip-hop.

00:32:53.000 --> 00:32:54.291
So I love the story of hip-hop.

00:32:54.291 --> 00:32:55.580
So forgive me if you know it.

00:32:55.580 --> 00:32:57.320
How we got hip-hop is
basically this idea

00:32:57.320 --> 00:32:58.580
of cognitive friction.

00:32:58.580 --> 00:33:01.040
Started with these dance
parties in the Bronx,

00:33:01.040 --> 00:33:03.950
where the party was
every weekend there would

00:33:03.950 --> 00:33:06.460
be dance hall where
they'd have two deejays,

00:33:06.460 --> 00:33:08.660
one DJ on one side, one
DJ on the other side.

00:33:08.660 --> 00:33:10.850
And the game was
see which DJ can

00:33:10.850 --> 00:33:13.447
get the party to dance on
their side of the dance hall.

00:33:13.447 --> 00:33:15.780
So this was all about what
music you brought every week,

00:33:15.780 --> 00:33:17.134
how loud your speakers were.

00:33:17.134 --> 00:33:19.550
People would show up every
week, and they'd do this party.

00:33:19.550 --> 00:33:23.490
And they'd pay money, and
then the DJs were all happy.

00:33:23.490 --> 00:33:25.100
And after a while,
the DJs started

00:33:25.100 --> 00:33:29.750
having these hype guys
announcing the next song.

00:33:29.750 --> 00:33:32.420
They'd try to drag people over
to their side of the party.

00:33:32.420 --> 00:33:33.230
And so they'd say,
hey, everybody,

00:33:33.230 --> 00:33:34.370
my DJ's got this great song.

00:33:34.370 --> 00:33:34.994
Come over here.

00:33:34.994 --> 00:33:36.220
Come dance.

00:33:36.220 --> 00:33:39.650
And then the MCs would start
getting really into it,

00:33:39.650 --> 00:33:42.480
and they'd do these sort
of fun couplets, where

00:33:42.480 --> 00:33:43.550
they'd be like--

00:33:43.550 --> 00:33:46.220
forgive me anyone
who watches this.

00:33:46.220 --> 00:33:48.600
They'd be like, hey, ho,
put your hands in the air,

00:33:48.600 --> 00:33:50.680
come on, y'all, like
that sort of thing.

00:33:50.680 --> 00:33:53.660
And one week, this
guy named Busy Bee,

00:33:53.660 --> 00:33:56.120
who was sort of
everyone's favorite,

00:33:56.120 --> 00:33:58.190
he was there hyping up his DJ.

00:33:58.190 --> 00:34:01.340
And he goes, ba-ditty, bada,
bang, de bang, diggy-diggy,

00:34:01.340 --> 00:34:04.080
put your hands in the air,
ya'll, that whole thing.

00:34:04.080 --> 00:34:08.050
And this other guy, the
other DJs hype man, his name

00:34:08.050 --> 00:34:11.389
was Kool Moe Dee, instead
of doing the same thing,

00:34:11.389 --> 00:34:15.020
like, hey, ho, come on, he
says, now hold on, Busy Bee,

00:34:15.020 --> 00:34:17.600
I don't mean to be bold, but
put that ba-ditty-ba bullshit

00:34:17.600 --> 00:34:18.710
on hold.

00:34:18.710 --> 00:34:20.460
And it was like,
[IMITATES RECORD SCRATCH]

00:34:20.460 --> 00:34:21.469
like record scratch.

00:34:21.469 --> 00:34:22.429
And everyone was like, what?

00:34:22.429 --> 00:34:23.804
And then he goes
for five minutes

00:34:23.804 --> 00:34:27.785
just with this rhyming
poetry, insulting Busy Bee

00:34:27.785 --> 00:34:29.792
and his music and his DJ.

00:34:29.792 --> 00:34:30.750
And everyone went nuts.

00:34:30.750 --> 00:34:32.639
They thought it was the
greatest thing ever.

00:34:32.639 --> 00:34:34.550
So then the next week-- you
imagine if that happens to you,

00:34:34.550 --> 00:34:37.400
you don't show up the next week
saying, hey, ho, ba-ditty-ba.

00:34:37.400 --> 00:34:38.780
You come prepared.

00:34:38.780 --> 00:34:41.719
And this turned into this
weekly battle of wits.

00:34:41.719 --> 00:34:44.570
And then it also turned into
this weekly battle of dance.

00:34:44.570 --> 00:34:46.969
And you didn't show up every
week with the same stuff

00:34:46.969 --> 00:34:47.570
as last week.

00:34:47.570 --> 00:34:49.760
You showed up ready
for the battle.

00:34:49.760 --> 00:34:53.154
And Jay-Z was actually on
Letterman's new Netflix show

00:34:53.154 --> 00:34:54.320
recently talking about this.

00:34:54.320 --> 00:34:57.214
And he said, you know,
this wasn't actually

00:34:57.214 --> 00:34:58.380
about destroying each other.

00:34:58.380 --> 00:34:59.504
It was all about the party.

00:34:59.504 --> 00:35:01.420
We knew that this
competition, this battle

00:35:01.420 --> 00:35:03.080
was about making
this party better.

00:35:03.080 --> 00:35:04.150
We're all in on it.

00:35:04.150 --> 00:35:06.650
You wanted to win, but
more people showed up,

00:35:06.650 --> 00:35:09.020
we all made more money,
everyone made more--

00:35:09.020 --> 00:35:11.220
Jay-Z was young
when this happened.

00:35:11.220 --> 00:35:13.022
But that's what this is about.

00:35:13.022 --> 00:35:15.230
But it got to the point
where the DJs started hacking

00:35:15.230 --> 00:35:16.280
their equipment.

00:35:16.280 --> 00:35:18.680
Grandmaster Flash soldered
on a little switch

00:35:18.680 --> 00:35:20.691
into his record
player to fade down

00:35:20.691 --> 00:35:22.940
the music so he could fade
up music on another record.

00:35:22.940 --> 00:35:24.023
Everyone blew their minds.

00:35:24.023 --> 00:35:25.630
Everyone then tried to do that.

00:35:25.630 --> 00:35:27.707
When they started doing
electronic samples,

00:35:27.707 --> 00:35:29.540
DJ's would actually
crack open the equipment

00:35:29.540 --> 00:35:31.665
and add more memory so they
could do better samples

00:35:31.665 --> 00:35:32.870
and beat the other guy.

00:35:32.870 --> 00:35:36.500
And so out of this
competition, this friction,

00:35:36.500 --> 00:35:39.230
was born not only hip-hop,
but all of the genres of music

00:35:39.230 --> 00:35:43.300
that came after it, R&amp;B and
whatever the hell dubstep is.

00:35:43.300 --> 00:35:48.860
And also, actual innovation
in computers came from this.

00:35:48.860 --> 00:35:51.470
And so this is again
kind of a literal example

00:35:51.470 --> 00:35:53.090
of how innovation
is actually born

00:35:53.090 --> 00:35:56.300
from the friction between the
different ways of our thinking.

00:35:56.300 --> 00:35:58.020
You didn't show up
doing the same thing.

00:35:58.020 --> 00:35:59.570
That would have been dumb.

00:35:59.570 --> 00:36:02.090
But if it wasn't for this
competition, this battle

00:36:02.090 --> 00:36:04.631
of wits, we wouldn't have got
hip-hop and all the things that

00:36:04.631 --> 00:36:05.200
came with it.

00:36:05.200 --> 00:36:07.490
So I kind of chart
out if you look

00:36:07.490 --> 00:36:09.946
at potential energy
between a group of people,

00:36:09.946 --> 00:36:12.320
you can sort of chart it like
this as like a rubber band.

00:36:12.320 --> 00:36:13.490
The more you
stretch, the more you

00:36:13.490 --> 00:36:15.980
put tension on a rubber band,
the more potential energy

00:36:15.980 --> 00:36:16.571
it has.

00:36:16.571 --> 00:36:17.570
Same thing with a group.

00:36:17.570 --> 00:36:19.790
A group of people with different
perspectives and heuristics

00:36:19.790 --> 00:36:21.456
are like people pulling
on a rubber band

00:36:21.456 --> 00:36:22.950
from different sides.

00:36:22.950 --> 00:36:24.920
Now we're all afraid
of the part where

00:36:24.920 --> 00:36:26.270
the rubber band snaps, right?

00:36:26.270 --> 00:36:27.350
It hurts.

00:36:27.350 --> 00:36:29.919
But if we don't go
that far, then there's

00:36:29.919 --> 00:36:30.710
a lot of potential.

00:36:30.710 --> 00:36:33.168
You can shoot the rubber band
really far or whatever it is.

00:36:33.168 --> 00:36:35.789
You can make a whole
industry that hip-hop made.

00:36:35.789 --> 00:36:37.580
And anyone who knows
the history of hip-hop

00:36:37.580 --> 00:36:40.400
knows that at some point
it actually did go too far.

00:36:40.400 --> 00:36:41.240
Things got personal.

00:36:41.240 --> 00:36:42.906
There's an East coast,
West coast thing.

00:36:42.906 --> 00:36:44.566
People actually got murdered.

00:36:44.566 --> 00:36:46.940
And the whole music industry
stepped back and said, well,

00:36:46.940 --> 00:36:47.780
what are we doing this for?

00:36:47.780 --> 00:36:48.571
What is this about?

00:36:48.571 --> 00:36:51.020
Is this about elevating the
party, making better music?

00:36:51.020 --> 00:36:55.610
Or is this about literally
trying to kill each other.

00:36:55.610 --> 00:36:57.985
So this is what we're all
afraid of when we work together

00:36:57.985 --> 00:36:59.568
with people who are
different than us,

00:36:59.568 --> 00:37:02.150
is this tension, this friction,
which could lead to snapping

00:37:02.150 --> 00:37:03.770
or could make it
an unsafe place.

00:37:03.770 --> 00:37:05.228
But this is actually
the thing that

00:37:05.228 --> 00:37:07.070
gives us all the
potential in the world,

00:37:07.070 --> 00:37:08.990
combining our perspectives
and our heuristics,

00:37:08.990 --> 00:37:12.350
which are shaped by our life
experiences and who we are.

00:37:12.350 --> 00:37:15.320
This is how we get into
this zone of possibility.

00:37:15.320 --> 00:37:17.190
And this is where
innovation happens.

00:37:17.190 --> 00:37:21.760
So in a group of people,
if you're a leader,

00:37:21.760 --> 00:37:23.790
you want to get the
group into this zone

00:37:23.790 --> 00:37:25.122
of cognitive friction.

00:37:25.122 --> 00:37:27.330
You want to push things out
of that destruction zone,

00:37:27.330 --> 00:37:29.082
and you want to
depressurize things.

00:37:29.082 --> 00:37:31.290
You want to prevent also
this inertia from happening,

00:37:31.290 --> 00:37:33.420
where everyone gets
along too famously, where

00:37:33.420 --> 00:37:36.660
all of our ideas, we all agree,
no one is willing to speak up

00:37:36.660 --> 00:37:40.170
or to battle or be someone's
intellectual opponent.

00:37:40.170 --> 00:37:42.600
And so the best leaders,
the best groups actually

00:37:42.600 --> 00:37:46.047
try and push things into
this zone of possibility.

00:37:46.047 --> 00:37:47.880
So I'm going to get
back to the pirate story

00:37:47.880 --> 00:37:49.650
in like three minutes.

00:37:49.650 --> 00:37:52.120
But the missing ingredient
for any of this to work--

00:37:52.120 --> 00:37:53.911
it's great if you have
cognitive diversity.

00:37:53.911 --> 00:37:55.530
It's great if you have friction.

00:37:55.530 --> 00:37:58.037
But if you're not willing to
change or adapt because of it,

00:37:58.037 --> 00:37:59.370
then what is it good for, right?

00:37:59.370 --> 00:38:00.786
You can have an
argument, and then

00:38:00.786 --> 00:38:02.900
if no one changes their
minds, what is it for?

00:38:02.900 --> 00:38:04.941
So this thing called
intellectual humility, which

00:38:04.941 --> 00:38:08.430
is the last few
chapters of my book,

00:38:08.430 --> 00:38:10.680
get into this idea of
being able to transcend

00:38:10.680 --> 00:38:13.475
your own way of thinking,
which is extremely hard,

00:38:13.475 --> 00:38:14.850
it turns out, for
the human brain

00:38:14.850 --> 00:38:17.160
to do once we've
become entrenched

00:38:17.160 --> 00:38:18.641
in a way of doing something.

00:38:18.641 --> 00:38:20.640
So, to get at that, I
want to tell a quick story

00:38:20.640 --> 00:38:22.042
about these two guys.

00:38:22.042 --> 00:38:24.000
They were two engineers
that were collaborating

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:25.260
about 100 years ago.

00:38:25.260 --> 00:38:29.820
And if you walked by their
shop on any given day,

00:38:29.820 --> 00:38:31.650
you'd hear them
yelling at each other.

00:38:31.650 --> 00:38:33.312
Their assistants,
their neighbors

00:38:33.312 --> 00:38:34.770
were really worried
that these guys

00:38:34.770 --> 00:38:36.210
were going to punch
each other out or kill

00:38:36.210 --> 00:38:37.390
each other at some point.

00:38:37.390 --> 00:38:41.280
You walk by, and it's screaming,
yelling, arguing all the time.

00:38:41.280 --> 00:38:43.830
But then if you'd walk by
their shop around lunchtime,

00:38:43.830 --> 00:38:45.896
you'd hear nothing, like quiet.

00:38:45.896 --> 00:38:48.270
But then after lunch, the
screaming, yelling would start.

00:38:48.270 --> 00:38:50.040
Basically what
these guys would do

00:38:50.040 --> 00:38:52.340
is they'd be working
on a problem,

00:38:52.340 --> 00:38:55.040
they'd be trying to figure
out the solution to something,

00:38:55.040 --> 00:38:57.765
and they'd purposely start
these really intense arguments,

00:38:57.765 --> 00:39:01.500
where they'd take extreme sides
and really yell at each other.

00:39:01.500 --> 00:39:03.210
But then at lunchtime,
they would stop,

00:39:03.210 --> 00:39:05.100
they'd eat their
sandwiches, and then

00:39:05.100 --> 00:39:07.180
they would switch
sides of the argument.

00:39:07.180 --> 00:39:09.388
So one guy had to argue the
other guy's side and vice

00:39:09.388 --> 00:39:09.970
versa.

00:39:09.970 --> 00:39:12.150
And this forced them
to let go of their need

00:39:12.150 --> 00:39:15.114
to be right, to detach their
ego from their intellect

00:39:15.114 --> 00:39:17.280
in whatever this argument
was and forced them to use

00:39:17.280 --> 00:39:18.540
a little bit of
intellectual humility

00:39:18.540 --> 00:39:20.580
so they could amp up
this cognitive function,

00:39:20.580 --> 00:39:22.290
they could have these
really intense debates.

00:39:22.290 --> 00:39:23.700
But it didn't matter if
you lost, because you were

00:39:23.700 --> 00:39:24.908
going to switch sides anyway.

00:39:24.908 --> 00:39:26.850
So it was about pushing
that party forward.

00:39:26.850 --> 00:39:30.452
And this might sound like
a hostile work environment,

00:39:30.452 --> 00:39:32.660
if you think about yelling
at your coworkers all day.

00:39:32.660 --> 00:39:33.720
But you'll forgive
them when you learn

00:39:33.720 --> 00:39:35.640
that these are the two guys
that invented the airplane.

00:39:35.640 --> 00:39:37.120
This is Orville
and Wilbur Wright.

00:39:37.120 --> 00:39:38.250
And maybe they
could actually have

00:39:38.250 --> 00:39:40.583
the fights be really intense
because they were brothers.

00:39:40.583 --> 00:39:42.030
They knew that they were family.

00:39:42.030 --> 00:39:43.950
They would be OK.

00:39:43.950 --> 00:39:45.842
But they deliberately
did this because they

00:39:45.842 --> 00:39:47.550
wanted to get to the
top of the mountain,

00:39:47.550 --> 00:39:50.880
but they knew that when
you're ready to murder Wilbur,

00:39:50.880 --> 00:39:52.630
you've got to switch sides.

00:39:52.630 --> 00:39:53.955
You need to change.

00:39:53.955 --> 00:39:55.830
So this is their little
trick for doing this,

00:39:55.830 --> 00:39:57.780
for unlocking this equation.

00:39:57.780 --> 00:39:59.490
So, moral of the
story is we need

00:39:59.490 --> 00:40:02.040
to be able to change our
minds because of this stuff.

00:40:02.040 --> 00:40:03.660
We need to value the friction.

00:40:03.660 --> 00:40:07.140
We need to value the
cognitive diversity

00:40:07.140 --> 00:40:09.120
if we want to get
anywhere further than we

00:40:09.120 --> 00:40:10.350
can go on our own.

00:40:10.350 --> 00:40:12.100
But we need to be able
to change to do it.

00:40:12.100 --> 00:40:14.216
So this in a nutshell
explains all the reasons

00:40:14.216 --> 00:40:15.840
corporate America
sucks and why we have

00:40:15.840 --> 00:40:17.720
so many problems in the world.

00:40:17.720 --> 00:40:19.470
And it's a starting
point for figuring out

00:40:19.470 --> 00:40:22.110
how we can make our
teams and our communities

00:40:22.110 --> 00:40:26.010
and societies better, actually
leaning into these things.

00:40:26.010 --> 00:40:29.130
So speaking of impressive
teams, the British army

00:40:29.130 --> 00:40:30.690
was fucking dope.

00:40:30.690 --> 00:40:33.582
They had 20,000 troops
that just beat Napoleon.

00:40:33.582 --> 00:40:35.040
And they figured
out pretty quickly

00:40:35.040 --> 00:40:36.930
that Jean Laffite wasn't
going to show up to guide them

00:40:36.930 --> 00:40:37.530
through the swamps.

00:40:37.530 --> 00:40:39.450
So they're like, great,
our cover is blown.

00:40:39.450 --> 00:40:43.871
But we have 7-1 odds against
these misfits in this party

00:40:43.871 --> 00:40:44.370
city.

00:40:44.370 --> 00:40:46.050
They're probably
all drunk anyway.

00:40:46.050 --> 00:40:48.231
So, they rode their
boats through the swamp.

00:40:48.231 --> 00:40:50.730
And they make camp right outside
of the city of New Orleans,

00:40:50.730 --> 00:40:52.605
ready to just use like
a British-style ground

00:40:52.605 --> 00:40:54.990
invasion, rows and rows
of thousands of soldiers

00:40:54.990 --> 00:40:58.950
and their great outfits
to just overrun the city,

00:40:58.950 --> 00:41:00.100
take over America.

00:41:00.100 --> 00:41:01.600
So that night as
they're camped out,

00:41:01.600 --> 00:41:06.630
they're getting ready for
