a pirate ship, in fact, floats
down the Mississippi River

00:41:10.290 --> 00:41:14.100
and docks right off the
shore of this camp of 20,000

00:41:14.100 --> 00:41:16.020
British soldiers.

00:41:16.020 --> 00:41:17.260
And it stops.

00:41:17.260 --> 00:41:18.787
And it waits.

00:41:18.787 --> 00:41:19.620
And it does nothing.

00:41:19.620 --> 00:41:22.100
And they fired some
warning shots at it.

00:41:22.100 --> 00:41:23.850
And the British decided,
they're like, oh,

00:41:23.850 --> 00:41:25.560
this little tiny ship, whatever.

00:41:25.560 --> 00:41:28.250
It's probably a
fisherman or some idiot.

00:41:28.250 --> 00:41:29.470
And so they go to bed.

00:41:29.470 --> 00:41:31.470
They have their sentries
up, but they go to bed,

00:41:31.470 --> 00:41:32.850
and they're watching it.

00:41:32.850 --> 00:41:34.720
And then the pirate
ship opens fire,

00:41:34.720 --> 00:41:37.230
just cannons after
cannons after cannons,

00:41:37.230 --> 00:41:38.936
cannon balls into the camp.

00:41:38.936 --> 00:41:40.560
They're not making
a dent on this army,

00:41:40.560 --> 00:41:42.270
but it's really hard to sleep.

00:41:42.270 --> 00:41:44.576
And they have to kind of
batten down, hide in the mud.

00:41:44.576 --> 00:41:46.200
They get done with
all the cannonballs.

00:41:46.200 --> 00:41:51.250
They start shooting cutlery and
random things into the camp.

00:41:51.250 --> 00:41:54.555
And so this is very annoying
to the British army, obviously.

00:41:54.555 --> 00:41:56.430
There's no way that
you're going to still win

00:41:56.430 --> 00:41:58.150
7-1 odds with this going on.

00:41:58.150 --> 00:42:01.260
But they're ruining their
sleep, really obnoxious.

00:42:01.260 --> 00:42:04.200
And then meanwhile, anyone
who ran into the woods to pee

00:42:04.200 --> 00:42:06.480
would run into this
guy and get tomahawked.

00:42:06.480 --> 00:42:09.240
So these Choctaw Braves
were out there basically

00:42:09.240 --> 00:42:12.510
murdering anyone who got
too far away from camp.

00:42:12.510 --> 00:42:16.140
And they had taught their
rivals, the Dirty Shirt

00:42:16.140 --> 00:42:18.370
Tennessee hunters,
had to climb trees

00:42:18.370 --> 00:42:21.750
and to sit in the top of a
tree and assassinate anyone

00:42:21.750 --> 00:42:24.474
who was a target, basically.

00:42:24.474 --> 00:42:26.640
So the British thought this
was really unchivalrous.

00:42:26.640 --> 00:42:28.723
Again, they're not making
a huge dent in the army,

00:42:28.723 --> 00:42:30.190
but this is really
bad for morale.

00:42:30.190 --> 00:42:31.856
They thought it was
really unchivalrous.

00:42:31.856 --> 00:42:33.787
This is not how noble
wars are fought.

00:42:33.787 --> 00:42:36.120
You're supposed to line up,
look each other in the eyes,

00:42:36.120 --> 00:42:36.703
and do battle.

00:42:36.703 --> 00:42:38.257
This is how war was done.

00:42:38.257 --> 00:42:40.090
So Colonel Nichols, the
head of the British,

00:42:40.090 --> 00:42:43.606
he sent an envoy to Jackson
that night to cordially

00:42:43.606 --> 00:42:45.480
request that they meet
in the field of battle

00:42:45.480 --> 00:42:47.470
and fight like men of honor.

00:42:47.470 --> 00:42:51.056
And Jackson literally
said, go fuck yourself.

00:42:51.056 --> 00:42:52.680
And he sent this
envoy back, and he was

00:42:52.680 --> 00:42:53.929
like, you're invading my land.

00:42:53.929 --> 00:42:55.020
Fuck you.

00:42:55.020 --> 00:42:58.697
So in the morning, the
British, demoralized, tired,

00:42:58.697 --> 00:43:00.780
their friends are being
murdered in the night when

00:43:00.780 --> 00:43:03.209
they go to pee, everyone is
afraid to pee, they get up,

00:43:03.209 --> 00:43:03.750
they line up.

00:43:03.750 --> 00:43:05.580
They're like, OK,
we're going to do this.

00:43:05.580 --> 00:43:08.310
So Jean Laffite and
the freemen of color

00:43:08.310 --> 00:43:11.070
teamed up to build a
moat and a dirt rampart.

00:43:11.070 --> 00:43:14.190
So they lined the city
with this rampart.

00:43:14.190 --> 00:43:17.460
They built it out into the
swamp kind of strategically so

00:43:17.460 --> 00:43:19.380
that you had to go
over this rampart.

00:43:19.380 --> 00:43:21.360
It was only about this high.

00:43:21.360 --> 00:43:23.647
But this was their
defense force.

00:43:23.647 --> 00:43:25.980
And so the British, as they're
tromping through the mud,

00:43:25.980 --> 00:43:27.180
they're coming up on this.

00:43:27.180 --> 00:43:29.460
Now, this is how all
of the paintings show.

00:43:29.460 --> 00:43:32.790
They're like, oh, Andrew
Jackson boldly there,

00:43:32.790 --> 00:43:34.440
no one is shooting him.

00:43:34.440 --> 00:43:35.850
When I make the
movie about this,

00:43:35.850 --> 00:43:39.000
it's going to be Ryan Gosling,
which is who is really

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:41.910
up there manning the fort.

00:43:41.910 --> 00:43:45.780
Anyway, so what happened
is the Dirty Shirt riflemen

00:43:45.780 --> 00:43:48.300
were waiting in the trees
with their hunting rifles.

00:43:48.300 --> 00:43:50.640
And then Jackson
issued everyone whiskey

00:43:50.640 --> 00:43:54.280
supplied by the pirates
and the British charge.

00:43:54.280 --> 00:43:57.684
So they line up, they charge,
the defenders open fire.

00:43:57.684 --> 00:43:59.100
And it turned out
that the hunting

00:43:59.100 --> 00:44:03.309
rifles that these Dirty Shirt
riflemen had were really slow.

00:44:03.309 --> 00:44:05.350
They're not what you want
in this kind of battle.

00:44:05.350 --> 00:44:08.112
But they can shoot way further
than the British muskets.

00:44:08.112 --> 00:44:09.570
So they basically
just assassinated

00:44:09.570 --> 00:44:10.470
all of the British leaders.

00:44:10.470 --> 00:44:11.428
They all sat on horses.

00:44:11.428 --> 00:44:13.240
They were very visible targets.

00:44:13.240 --> 00:44:15.320
And you're not
supposed to do that.

00:44:15.320 --> 00:44:17.340
Like you're not
supposed to do that.

00:44:17.340 --> 00:44:18.980
They did it anyway.

00:44:18.980 --> 00:44:20.860
And so the British come up.

00:44:20.860 --> 00:44:21.860
And the worst part--

00:44:21.860 --> 00:44:24.431
they were so obedient,
this army, that you're

00:44:24.431 --> 00:44:25.430
supposed to take orders.

00:44:25.430 --> 00:44:28.260
You don't do anything that's,
you know-- their core value was

00:44:28.260 --> 00:44:29.960
like obedience to leadership.

00:44:29.960 --> 00:44:34.710
And this one platoon of
Scotsmen, the 90-second Scots,

00:44:34.710 --> 00:44:37.560
their captain yelled, halt!

00:44:37.560 --> 00:44:39.300
And then he got assassinated.

00:44:39.300 --> 00:44:40.830
And so they halted,
and they stayed

00:44:40.830 --> 00:44:43.304
there until like 800
of them got shot.

00:44:43.304 --> 00:44:45.720
Finally another captain came
in, and he was like, retreat!

00:44:45.720 --> 00:44:47.670
And they're like, thank God.

00:44:47.670 --> 00:44:51.480
And it's like this horrible kind
of case study of actually being

00:44:51.480 --> 00:44:53.827
stuck on a mountain peak
that is not the optimal one,

00:44:53.827 --> 00:44:56.160
even when probably some people
there could have spoke up

00:44:56.160 --> 00:44:58.160
and said, we should
probably not halt right now.

00:44:58.160 --> 00:45:01.810
Anyway, so the battle
was really awful.

00:45:01.810 --> 00:45:04.230
But after the smoke cleared
from the first assault,

00:45:04.230 --> 00:45:07.800
the British had lost 3,500
men, and the Americans

00:45:07.800 --> 00:45:11.180
had lost 333, so 7-1
odds against them

00:45:11.180 --> 00:45:13.930
but 10 to 1 casualties
in their favor.

00:45:13.930 --> 00:45:16.290
The British realized this
is going to be way too hard.

00:45:16.290 --> 00:45:17.789
We're not going to
make this happen.

00:45:17.789 --> 00:45:18.680
So they went home.

00:45:18.680 --> 00:45:19.930
And New Orleans threw a party.

00:45:19.930 --> 00:45:21.388
And this is the
reason why we don't

00:45:21.388 --> 00:45:24.000
have the queen on our $5
bill, is because of this.

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:27.030
And the party hasn't stopped,
by the way in New Orleans,

00:45:27.030 --> 00:45:29.080
because of this ragtag
group of misfits

00:45:29.080 --> 00:45:32.784
that defended that city in that
outrageous, overwhelming odds.

00:45:32.784 --> 00:45:34.950
So Andrew Jackson went on
to become a national hero,

00:45:34.950 --> 00:45:36.750
even though he's kind
of an awful person.

00:45:36.750 --> 00:45:37.860
They didn't have the
internet, so they

00:45:37.860 --> 00:45:39.970
couldn't find out that he
was a racist promise-breaker.

00:45:39.970 --> 00:45:41.594
He stiffed his
contractors, by the way.

00:45:41.594 --> 00:45:43.710
He didn't pay any of
the freemen of color

00:45:43.710 --> 00:45:45.960
even though he promised them.

00:45:45.960 --> 00:45:47.610
But he became president anyway.

00:45:47.610 --> 00:45:50.470
Edward Livingston, Saul Goodman,
became the Secretary of State.

00:45:50.470 --> 00:45:53.500
And John Laffite was pardoned
from all of his previous crimes

00:45:53.500 --> 00:45:54.980
he may have committed.

00:45:54.980 --> 00:45:56.730
So he went from stealing
votes to stealing

00:45:56.730 --> 00:45:58.920
the hearts of New Orleans'
beautiful married ladies.

00:45:58.920 --> 00:46:03.590
He became a man about town,
sort of a local socialite.

00:46:03.590 --> 00:46:05.612
Anyway, the lesson
from this story,

00:46:05.612 --> 00:46:08.070
it's not about Andrew Jackson's
leadership and that speech,

00:46:08.070 --> 00:46:12.540
let's get over our
differences and save the city.

00:46:12.540 --> 00:46:15.150
And it's not exactly about
the British colonel's hubris

00:46:15.150 --> 00:46:17.160
and actually this
really dumb approach

00:46:17.160 --> 00:46:18.870
to fighting this battle.

00:46:18.870 --> 00:46:21.390
But it's that in order
to beat the odds,

00:46:21.390 --> 00:46:23.370
a team of people who are
all good at their jobs

00:46:23.370 --> 00:46:26.070
and unified and
similar is not nearly

00:46:26.070 --> 00:46:28.650
going to be as effective as
a team with the right kinds

00:46:28.650 --> 00:46:31.110
of different ways of thinking
and working together,

00:46:31.110 --> 00:46:33.780
the different perspectives and
heuristics that this ragtag

00:46:33.780 --> 00:46:37.260
army taught each other,
the Choctaw Braves teaching

00:46:37.260 --> 00:46:39.450
the Dirty Shirts how
to do guerrilla war

00:46:39.450 --> 00:46:43.080
and assassinations, which
again this sort of ghastly.

00:46:43.080 --> 00:46:45.540
It was fighting this
like an Indian skirmish.

00:46:45.540 --> 00:46:48.120
It was the pirates
and their cannons

00:46:48.120 --> 00:46:50.100
and the freemen of
color all combining

00:46:50.100 --> 00:46:52.950
their different points
of view on war that

00:46:52.950 --> 00:46:54.480
helped them win this battle.

00:46:54.480 --> 00:46:56.610
And of course, war is
fought very differently now,

00:46:56.610 --> 00:47:00.741
but at the time, this was very
innovative and groundbreaking.

00:47:00.741 --> 00:47:03.240
So when Andrew Jackson says,
let's set aside our differences

00:47:03.240 --> 00:47:05.584
and fight this
battle, he might say

00:47:05.584 --> 00:47:07.500
or we might say some
things are more important

00:47:07.500 --> 00:47:10.470
than our differences, saving
the city, our superordinate goal

00:47:10.470 --> 00:47:11.799
that we're trying to achieve.

00:47:11.799 --> 00:47:13.590
But I think this is an
example of something

00:47:13.590 --> 00:47:15.120
that we all deep
down really know.

00:47:15.120 --> 00:47:17.610
Maybe the important
thing is our differences,

00:47:17.610 --> 00:47:18.870
and we should lean into that.

00:47:18.870 --> 00:47:20.370
So that's what I got.

00:47:20.370 --> 00:47:21.850
Thank you very much.

00:47:21.850 --> 00:47:24.539
And I would love to answer any
questions with any little time

00:47:24.539 --> 00:47:25.080
we have left.

00:47:25.080 --> 00:47:26.177
And thank you.

00:47:26.177 --> 00:47:30.650
[APPLAUSE]

00:47:35.140 --> 00:47:36.430
Is that the microphone?

00:47:36.430 --> 00:47:37.480
AUDIENCE: It is, yes.

00:47:37.480 --> 00:47:40.610
So I guess I'll ask the
first question then.

00:47:40.610 --> 00:47:43.580
Something that I've always
thought about is this--

00:47:43.580 --> 00:47:45.610
and first of all, thank
you for coming by.

00:47:45.610 --> 00:47:47.590
Always a pleasure.

00:47:47.590 --> 00:47:50.699
In regards to the
culture, I kind of

00:47:50.699 --> 00:47:52.990
feel like it's kind of a
contradiction, because we say,

00:47:52.990 --> 00:47:55.810
hey, Eric, bring
yourself and everything

00:47:55.810 --> 00:47:58.600
you are to our company, but
then adapt to this culture.

00:47:58.600 --> 00:48:02.030
So how do you navigate
that acclimation period?

00:48:02.030 --> 00:48:04.960
SHANE SNOW: Yeah, I think
that culture fit is actually

00:48:04.960 --> 00:48:08.050
a fairly poisonous concept.

00:48:08.050 --> 00:48:11.470
So there's research in the '70s
that they did that basically

00:48:11.470 --> 00:48:13.900
determined that
we're the most happy

00:48:13.900 --> 00:48:16.990
at work when we work with people
who have our same personality.

00:48:16.990 --> 00:48:19.180
And for 40 years,
we've of conflated that

00:48:19.180 --> 00:48:21.130
with being productive
and being good

00:48:21.130 --> 00:48:22.480
at solving problems together.

00:48:22.480 --> 00:48:24.229
Turns out that having
the same personality

00:48:24.229 --> 00:48:26.530
is actually not very
good for becoming smarter

00:48:26.530 --> 00:48:28.570
than the smartest
person in your group.

00:48:28.570 --> 00:48:31.200
And being happy at work
actually can be at odds

00:48:31.200 --> 00:48:33.700
with the thing that helps, which
is that cognitive friction.

00:48:33.700 --> 00:48:35.080
So I think that
culture fit is actually

00:48:35.080 --> 00:48:36.750
one of those things that
sounds like a good idea,

00:48:36.750 --> 00:48:37.460
because we want to be happy.

00:48:37.460 --> 00:48:38.230
We want to be comfortable.

00:48:38.230 --> 00:48:39.230
We want to have peace.

00:48:39.230 --> 00:48:41.510
But it's actually the
intellectual battle

00:48:41.510 --> 00:48:44.512
that helps us to stretch
and to become better.

00:48:44.512 --> 00:48:45.970
So I mean, I think
that culture add

00:48:45.970 --> 00:48:47.740
is actually the thing that
we should be talking about,

00:48:47.740 --> 00:48:49.990
and lots of people are
starting to talk about this.

00:48:49.990 --> 00:48:51.850
But there is this
question of what

00:48:51.850 --> 00:48:54.880
do we need to be
unified around, right?

00:48:54.880 --> 00:48:57.310
If we lean into the
thing that, hey,

00:48:57.310 --> 00:48:59.994
bringing different things that
are unique to the group is

00:48:59.994 --> 00:49:01.660
actually what's going
to help the group,

00:49:01.660 --> 00:49:03.868
if we combine in the right
ways and have the humility

00:49:03.868 --> 00:49:06.340
and all that, but then what
keeps that group together?

00:49:06.340 --> 00:49:08.920
And like in this story,
there was this purpose

00:49:08.920 --> 00:49:11.800
that everyone had,
which was this land

00:49:11.800 --> 00:49:12.872
that we want to protect.

00:49:12.872 --> 00:49:15.080
Sort of like the aliens show
up to destroy the Earth,

00:49:15.080 --> 00:49:17.150
we forget about our
borders, that sort of thing.

00:49:17.150 --> 00:49:19.291
We don't always have
that in a company.

00:49:19.291 --> 00:49:21.040
But ideally, you do
have a purpose of what

00:49:21.040 --> 00:49:22.206
you're trying to accomplish.

00:49:22.206 --> 00:49:26.654
I think Google has done really
well when the core values list

00:49:26.654 --> 00:49:27.820
was basically don't be evil.

00:49:27.820 --> 00:49:31.120
It's like, no duh, like
don't do wrong things.

00:49:31.120 --> 00:49:34.155
And then everyone at Google for
years and years could recite,

00:49:34.155 --> 00:49:36.280
our mission is to organize
the world's information.

00:49:36.280 --> 00:49:38.470
That's a pretty good purpose
that if you're actually

00:49:38.470 --> 00:49:42.340
down with and you leave
that path to getting there

00:49:42.340 --> 00:49:45.304
as flexible as possible,
then it allows room

00:49:45.304 --> 00:49:46.720
to be that sort
of band of misfits

00:49:46.720 --> 00:49:48.160
as long as you're
trying to do that.

00:49:48.160 --> 00:49:49.910
I think that purpose
is way more important

00:49:49.910 --> 00:49:53.170
than like lists of behaviors
we want everyone to do, right?

00:49:53.170 --> 00:49:56.440
And so I think to
some degree, Google

00:49:56.440 --> 00:49:58.570
is a very good example
of having done that right

00:49:58.570 --> 00:49:59.680
for many, many years.

00:49:59.680 --> 00:50:02.270
Obviously no company is perfect,
and there's lots of stuff.

00:50:02.270 --> 00:50:06.190
But I think the tendency we
have to say, great, you're

00:50:06.190 --> 00:50:11.386
new to the group, we value you
being here, now be like this,

00:50:11.386 --> 00:50:13.510
it just squashes the benefit
that we get out of it.

00:50:13.510 --> 00:50:14.950
It's like telling people
to get off the mountain

00:50:14.950 --> 00:50:16.220
and go on the other side.

00:50:16.220 --> 00:50:17.080
So I think that's
something important

00:50:17.080 --> 00:50:18.163
that we should talk about.

00:50:18.163 --> 00:50:21.090
At my company, we actually
banned the word culture fit.

00:50:21.090 --> 00:50:23.950
Any time someone said it,
we would use it as a--

00:50:23.950 --> 00:50:26.362
we would sort of pause any
meeting and say, all right,

00:50:26.362 --> 00:50:28.940
let's talk about how
we're not going to fit.

00:50:28.940 --> 00:50:31.150
And I think that's actually
kind of important, easier

00:50:31.150 --> 00:50:33.057
said than done,
but anyway, yeah.

00:50:33.057 --> 00:50:33.890
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:50:38.314 --> 00:50:40.105
SHANE SNOW: I sort of
like this microphone.

00:50:40.105 --> 00:50:41.137
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:50:41.137 --> 00:50:42.595
What's the difference
between like,

00:50:42.595 --> 00:50:47.740
I guess you said the poison of
culture fit versus you learning

00:50:47.740 --> 00:50:50.770
because you don't know anything
about the corporate life,

00:50:50.770 --> 00:50:53.680
like getting used to something
because you're learning it

00:50:53.680 --> 00:50:56.250
versus you keeping
with yourself?

00:50:56.250 --> 00:51:00.850
SHANE SNOW: Yeah, so you know
that whole mountain-range

00:51:00.850 --> 00:51:02.150
cartoon diagram?

00:51:02.150 --> 00:51:04.660
It also applies inside of
our own heads, too, right?

00:51:04.660 --> 00:51:07.600
As we learn, as we gain
experiences and education

00:51:07.600 --> 00:51:09.730
and work different
places, we're collecting

00:51:09.730 --> 00:51:11.771
potentially different
perspectives and heuristics

00:51:11.771 --> 00:51:13.720
that we can tap into.

00:51:13.720 --> 00:51:16.150
So even in your own work,
it is valuable, I think,

00:51:16.150 --> 00:51:17.816
to explore as much
of the mountain range

00:51:17.816 --> 00:51:18.880
as possible, right?

00:51:18.880 --> 00:51:20.890
So I think being curious
about things even

00:51:20.890 --> 00:51:24.230
if you don't find them useful
can actually be really good.

00:51:24.230 --> 00:51:26.020
You can draw lessons from them.

00:51:26.020 --> 00:51:29.940
Einstein was notoriously sort
of a loner when he did his work.

00:51:29.940 --> 00:51:32.440
He had like this rival that
pushed him, Niels Bohr.

00:51:32.440 --> 00:51:36.004
But he had a really diverse
set of inputs into his process.

00:51:36.004 --> 00:51:37.420
He was in a patent
office learning

00:51:37.420 --> 00:51:39.982
about all these different kinds
of industries and inventions.

00:51:39.982 --> 00:51:40.690
Certainly helped.

00:51:40.690 --> 00:51:42.100
And he was curious about them.

00:51:42.100 --> 00:51:44.440
But he also played the violin,
he was really into drama.

00:51:44.440 --> 00:51:49.840
Those things all helped broaden
his potential zone of friction

00:51:49.840 --> 00:51:51.130
inside his own head.

00:51:51.130 --> 00:51:53.704
So I think you're new
to an organization,

00:51:53.704 --> 00:51:55.870
actually learning how the
organization does function

00:51:55.870 --> 00:51:58.750
is really important,
but resisting the urge

00:51:58.750 --> 00:52:02.500
to have to fit and realizing
that if the organization is

00:52:02.500 --> 00:52:04.540
smart, even if
it's not, what you

00:52:04.540 --> 00:52:07.480
can bring that's outside of
the normal way of thinking

00:52:07.480 --> 00:52:10.240
to provoke new ways of thinking,
even if what you're bringing

00:52:10.240 --> 00:52:11.187
is not the best.

00:52:11.187 --> 00:52:12.520
You're on a lower mountain peak.

00:52:12.520 --> 00:52:14.256
Whatever you're
bringing can help

00:52:14.256 --> 00:52:15.380
explore more of that range.

00:52:15.380 --> 00:52:16.720
So I think that's important.

00:52:16.720 --> 00:52:19.000
In the book I have
a couple of chapters

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:21.580
about that idea of what
often looks crazy or useless

00:52:21.580 --> 00:52:24.580
can actually be really helpful
in solving problems, which

00:52:24.580 --> 00:52:26.890
is an excuse for
including people who

00:52:26.890 --> 00:52:29.890
are more novices
in a deliberation

00:52:29.890 --> 00:52:32.200
process or
problem-solving process.

00:52:32.200 --> 00:52:34.060
With the cops thing,
there's research

00:52:34.060 --> 00:52:36.390
about how when you put an
old cop with a young cop,

00:52:36.390 --> 00:52:38.500
sort of like a buddy
cop movie thing,

00:52:38.500 --> 00:52:40.600
that that partnership
will do better,

00:52:40.600 --> 00:52:43.440
just like when you put a male
cop and a female cop together.

00:52:43.440 --> 00:52:47.110
All cops tend to have a
different set of perspectives

00:52:47.110 --> 00:52:50.260
and heuristics, and new cops
tend to have a little bit more

00:52:50.260 --> 00:52:53.950
of that either no, we
gotta do it by the book

00:52:53.950 --> 00:52:55.780
or, well, why do we
have to do it that way?

00:52:55.780 --> 00:52:58.129
And that actually helps
with that process.

00:52:58.129 --> 00:52:59.920
Anyway, I'm kind of
rambling at this point,

00:52:59.920 --> 00:53:03.940
but I think all this stuff
as a pragmatic excuse

00:53:03.940 --> 00:53:05.930
for doing what's the
right thing to do,

00:53:05.930 --> 00:53:09.130
which is including people in--

00:53:09.130 --> 00:53:11.320
the more different
kinds of people

00:53:11.320 --> 00:53:13.990
that we have working on things,
the better chance we have

00:53:13.990 --> 00:53:15.081
of breaking through.

00:53:15.081 --> 00:53:16.330
It's also a good moral choice.

00:53:19.710 --> 00:53:21.636
Anyone else have a--

00:53:21.636 --> 00:53:22.136
yeah.

00:53:27.340 --> 00:53:31.430
AUDIENCE: So you talked a little
bit about like if you pass--

00:53:31.430 --> 00:53:33.120
you had that graph
where it was like,

00:53:33.120 --> 00:53:36.620
this is the area of destruction.

00:53:36.620 --> 00:53:39.625
Do you have any tips
or recommendations

00:53:39.625 --> 00:53:42.620
for how you prevent
from getting in that?

00:53:42.620 --> 00:53:44.120
I mean, is it
possible that you have

00:53:44.120 --> 00:53:47.210
too much cognitive diversity?

00:53:47.210 --> 00:53:49.850
Or is there other things
that you do recommend

00:53:49.850 --> 00:53:52.250
to not get into that area?

00:53:52.250 --> 00:53:54.390
SHANE SNOW: Yeah,
that's a great question.

00:53:54.390 --> 00:53:58.150
So is it possible to have
too much cognitive diversity?

00:53:58.150 --> 00:54:01.870
You need cognitive
diversity that's relevant.

00:54:01.870 --> 00:54:04.570
So like me being a pizza
driver when I'm age

00:54:04.570 --> 00:54:07.450
16 might actually not be
a relevant perspective

00:54:07.450 --> 00:54:10.600
to solving an algorithm
problem or something.

00:54:10.600 --> 00:54:11.440
It might be.

00:54:11.440 --> 00:54:14.140
You want to set yourself
up so you have the broadest

00:54:14.140 --> 00:54:15.495
array of possibilities.

00:54:15.495 --> 00:54:17.870
But some cognitive diversity
is not going to be relevant.

00:54:17.870 --> 00:54:20.174
And I think often
we make decisions

00:54:20.174 --> 00:54:22.090
on who to include in a
problem-solving process

00:54:22.090 --> 00:54:25.690
or on a team based on who was
on the team last or who's here,

00:54:25.690 --> 00:54:27.820
who's available,
or what's obvious.

00:54:27.820 --> 00:54:31.330
And I do think that
there's a very good excuse

00:54:31.330 --> 00:54:34.587
to include wildcards
and you should always

00:54:34.587 --> 00:54:36.920
include people who are going
to be affected by solutions

00:54:36.920 --> 00:54:38.687
to problems and all that.

00:54:38.687 --> 00:54:41.270
But you can have too many people
sitting around a table coming

00:54:41.270 --> 00:54:42.590
up with ideas, right?

00:54:42.590 --> 00:54:45.350
It's actually more
ideal to have a series

00:54:45.350 --> 00:54:48.156
of one-on-one processes
when you can amp up

00:54:48.156 --> 00:54:50.780
the debate and the friction with
different people and it's safe

00:54:50.780 --> 00:54:52.110
and all that.

00:54:52.110 --> 00:54:53.611
But the other
thing that you were

00:54:53.611 --> 00:54:55.610
asking about getting out
of the destruction zone

00:54:55.610 --> 00:54:58.550
or avoiding that,
usually the problem

00:54:58.550 --> 00:55:02.180
that most organizations have is
that you're so afraid of that

00:55:02.180 --> 00:55:03.320
that you pipe down.

00:55:03.320 --> 00:55:04.074
You quiet up.

00:55:04.074 --> 00:55:05.990
You have what's called
organizational silence.

00:55:05.990 --> 00:55:08.300
This is what kills mergers and
marriages and everything, is

00:55:08.300 --> 00:55:10.549
when you stop talking about
things that are important,

00:55:10.549 --> 00:55:12.660
because you're afraid
of the conflict.

00:55:12.660 --> 00:55:15.670
But there's a few things, and
I get into this in the book.

00:55:15.670 --> 00:55:17.840
There's a couple
of things that are

00:55:17.840 --> 00:55:22.040
easy to do to reduce the
tension in our relationship

00:55:22.040 --> 00:55:24.380
between people that have a
lot of cognitive diversity

00:55:24.380 --> 00:55:27.980
and maybe that have fear of
their differences in general.

00:55:27.980 --> 00:55:29.270
One of them is playing.

00:55:29.270 --> 00:55:32.810
So it turns out that
play and humor simulates

00:55:32.810 --> 00:55:34.970
the situation of anxiety.

00:55:34.970 --> 00:55:37.190
But your brain knows
when you're playing

00:55:37.190 --> 00:55:39.270
or when there's a joke
that it's not real

00:55:39.270 --> 00:55:40.820
and it's not actually dangerous.

00:55:40.820 --> 00:55:42.920
And so if you play
with a group of people,

00:55:42.920 --> 00:55:47.240
you'll end up putting them in
your psychological in-group

00:55:47.240 --> 00:55:48.410
after a while.

00:55:48.410 --> 00:55:51.470
And they've done all sorts
of experiments in this.

00:55:51.470 --> 00:55:53.420
Another thing that
I'm personally

00:55:53.420 --> 00:55:56.210
really passionate
about is storytelling.

00:55:56.210 --> 00:55:57.680
The neuroscience
of storytelling is

00:55:57.680 --> 00:56:02.900
something that has been recently
dove into by neuroeconomists.

00:56:02.900 --> 00:56:06.560
Basically the summary is when
you learn someone's story,

00:56:06.560 --> 00:56:09.830
especially you learn something
vulnerable and emotional,

00:56:09.830 --> 00:56:11.630
an emotion that you
can identify with,

00:56:11.630 --> 00:56:13.700
your brain generates
oxytocin, which

00:56:13.700 --> 00:56:16.280
is the empathy drug, which
makes you care about them.

00:56:16.280 --> 00:56:18.080
And they've done
tons of experiments

00:56:18.080 --> 00:56:19.250
that basically show--

00:56:19.250 --> 00:56:20.690
and some companies
like BlackRock

00:56:20.690 --> 00:56:24.064
have actually incorporated
this into a corporate setting.

00:56:24.064 --> 00:56:25.480
If you and I don't
know each other

00:56:25.480 --> 00:56:27.620
and maybe for
whatever reason we're

00:56:27.620 --> 00:56:30.680
nervous about each other's very
different ideas or perspectives

00:56:30.680 --> 00:56:34.910
or I grew up in a place where
you would be scared of me,

00:56:34.910 --> 00:56:38.840
if I learn your story, then
I'll become more comfortable,

00:56:38.840 --> 00:56:41.870
and we can actually have more
of that cognitive friction

00:56:41.870 --> 00:56:44.042
between us, and it's safe.

00:56:44.042 --> 00:56:46.250
So you build trust through
learning people's stories.

00:56:46.250 --> 00:56:48.350
And you know that thing
in the "New York Times"

00:56:48.350 --> 00:56:49.808
a couple of years
ago where it said

00:56:49.808 --> 00:56:52.730
to fall in love with anyone, ask
each other these 30 questions?

00:56:52.730 --> 00:56:53.820
Anyone see that?

00:56:53.820 --> 00:56:56.180
This is a really a popular
story that basically is like,

00:56:56.180 --> 00:56:58.340
if you go through these 30
questions with a stranger,

00:56:58.340 --> 00:57:00.048
you will basically
fall in love with them

00:57:00.048 --> 00:57:03.830
or you'll be much more likely
to have feelings for them.

00:57:03.830 --> 00:57:05.330
All of those questions
are basically

00:57:05.330 --> 00:57:07.700
asking you a series of
increasingly vulnerable stories

00:57:07.700 --> 00:57:09.659
about yourself, what's
the last time you cried?

00:57:09.659 --> 00:57:11.325
What's something that
you wish you would

00:57:11.325 --> 00:57:12.500
have done in your childhood?

00:57:12.500 --> 00:57:14.930
You can't share those kinds
of stories with people

00:57:14.930 --> 00:57:18.330
without developing
empathy and trust.

00:57:18.330 --> 00:57:20.810
And that allows
you to go further

00:57:20.810 --> 00:57:23.380
in your intellectual
battle without it devolving

00:57:23.380 --> 00:57:24.380
into something personal.

00:57:24.380 --> 00:57:26.390
The Wright brothers,
they loved each other,

00:57:26.390 --> 00:57:29.485
and they knew each other
and had this deep affection

00:57:29.485 --> 00:57:30.110
for each other.

00:57:30.110 --> 00:57:31.700
It allowed them to go further.

00:57:31.700 --> 00:57:34.790
So things like that are
psychological tricks

00:57:34.790 --> 00:57:36.590
that you can do.

00:57:36.590 --> 00:57:39.440
Easier to do in a team setting,
in a small group of people,

00:57:39.440 --> 00:57:41.702
or in a company then in like
society like on Facebook

00:57:41.702 --> 00:57:43.160
or like, hey, let's
all play a game

00:57:43.160 --> 00:57:45.770
so we can stop arguing about
Democrats versus Republicans.

00:57:45.770 --> 00:57:47.570
Like that's a little bit harder.

00:57:47.570 --> 00:57:52.230
But there's some real power
to learning people's stories.

00:57:52.230 --> 00:57:54.062
But, yeah, I mean,
that's basically

00:57:54.062 --> 00:57:55.520
the game that's
afoot, is how do we

00:57:55.520 --> 00:57:57.984
keep our relationships
in that zone

00:57:57.984 --> 00:57:59.150
without it getting personal?

00:58:02.012 --> 00:58:04.530
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
Do you hear me?

00:58:04.530 --> 00:58:07.120
OK, so speaking of
stories, I really

00:58:07.120 --> 00:58:10.120
love the way you started with
a story and put everything

00:58:10.120 --> 00:58:11.050
in that context.

00:58:11.050 --> 00:58:12.054
SHANE SNOW: Thanks.

00:58:12.054 --> 00:58:14.470
AUDIENCE: Wanted to ask you
about that crucial step, which

00:58:14.470 --> 00:58:17.791
is people need to
be flexible and be

00:58:17.791 --> 00:58:20.290
able to change their opinion
in order for progress to exist.

00:58:20.290 --> 00:58:23.230
So what would you
recommend doing in a set-up

00:58:23.230 --> 00:58:26.457
where do you see that there is
resistance from certain people

00:58:26.457 --> 00:58:27.790
that they don't want to do that?

00:58:27.790 --> 00:58:29.090
And then what do you do?

00:58:29.090 --> 00:58:30.714
SHANE SNOW: Yeah, so
I think if there's

00:58:30.714 --> 00:58:32.560
one skill everyone
in the world could

00:58:32.560 --> 00:58:35.200
learn that would make everything
better, like all of work

00:58:35.200 --> 00:58:38.567
and all of society, it would
be intellectual humility.

00:58:38.567 --> 00:58:40.150
And intellectual
humility is something

00:58:40.150 --> 00:58:42.316
that philosophers have
talked about for a long time,

00:58:42.316 --> 00:58:43.900
but it's only in
2017 that we could

00:58:43.900 --> 00:58:46.904
actually-- we had an
assessment for measuring

00:58:46.904 --> 00:58:47.820
intellectual humility.

00:58:47.820 --> 00:58:50.600
And it breaks down
to a few categories.

00:58:50.600 --> 00:58:52.480
So if you go to
shanesnow.com/IH,

00:58:52.480 --> 00:58:56.110
you can take the actual test
that they developed and see

00:58:56.110 --> 00:58:58.580
what areas you need to improve.

00:58:58.580 --> 00:59:01.250
So for me, separating my ego
from my intellect is very hard.

00:59:01.250 --> 00:59:03.130
If you convince me
I'm wrong, I will

00:59:03.130 --> 00:59:06.440
be more likely than the average
person to revise my viewpoint.

00:59:06.440 --> 00:59:08.800
But it will hurt
bad, so that makes

00:59:08.800 --> 00:59:11.530
me harder to collaborate with.

00:59:11.530 --> 00:59:12.874
So that's one thing.

00:59:12.874 --> 00:59:14.290
If you're dealing
with someone who

00:59:14.290 --> 00:59:15.970
you know is going
to be resistant,

00:59:15.970 --> 00:59:17.680
there's a few tricks.

00:59:17.680 --> 00:59:22.090
You want to prime them to not
get into personal battle mode

00:59:22.090 --> 00:59:24.280
and to be in more
intellectual battle mode.

00:59:24.280 --> 00:59:26.740
My favorite thing of
late is Ben Franklin

00:59:26.740 --> 00:59:28.536
had this trick that he would do.

00:59:28.536 --> 00:59:30.160
He knew most the time
he's the smartest

00:59:30.160 --> 00:59:31.420
person he's interacting with.

00:59:31.420 --> 00:59:32.920
But he also knew
that he's not going

00:59:32.920 --> 00:59:36.250
to get better if he acted that
way and that he could be wrong.

00:59:36.250 --> 00:59:38.587
So when he was going to express
an argument of something

00:59:38.587 --> 00:59:41.170
that he felt very strongly about
or tried to persuade someone,

00:59:41.170 --> 00:59:43.790
he'd always start
with, I could be wrong,

00:59:43.790 --> 00:59:46.310
but-- and then he'd hit
him with the argument.

00:59:46.310 --> 00:59:48.700
And what it does is
it primes that person

00:59:48.700 --> 00:59:50.530
to feel like it's not
going to be personal

00:59:50.530 --> 00:59:51.961
if they prove you wrong.

00:59:51.961 --> 00:59:54.460
And they're less on their heels
when you start the argument.

00:59:54.460 --> 00:59:57.670
He'd also shy away from using
absolutes, like it's always

00:59:57.670 --> 00:59:59.450
or it's certainly or whatever.

00:59:59.450 --> 01:00:02.380
So there's always
room for change.

01:00:02.380 --> 01:00:06.700
But for him, it helped because
if you proved him wrong,

01:00:06.700 --> 01:00:07.592
he was still right.

01:00:07.592 --> 01:00:09.550
He could tell his ego,
I said I could be wrong,

01:00:09.550 --> 01:00:11.800
and I was, so I'm right.

01:00:11.800 --> 01:00:14.740
And there's stuff
like that you can do.

01:00:14.740 --> 01:00:18.029
I just wrote a post
in my newsletter--

01:00:18.029 --> 01:00:19.570
you can go to my
website and see it--

01:00:19.570 --> 01:00:22.660
about a few other strategies
for that sort of thing,

01:00:22.660 --> 01:00:24.180
keeping your identity small.

01:00:24.180 --> 01:00:27.220
What are things that you can do
to not bring your personal ego

01:00:27.220 --> 01:00:29.830
and identity into conversation.

01:00:29.830 --> 01:00:32.870
It's hard to force
someone else to do that.

01:00:32.870 --> 01:00:34.750
But the more that
you can get them

01:00:34.750 --> 01:00:38.440
to see you as a human being and
separate your ideas from who

01:00:38.440 --> 01:00:41.219
you are and see that
you're doing that with them

01:00:41.219 --> 01:00:43.510
and that you're allowing them
the opportunity to change

01:00:43.510 --> 01:00:45.659
your mind, that often rubs off.

01:00:45.659 --> 01:00:47.200
Some people are not
going to do that,

01:00:47.200 --> 01:00:48.730
and then you've got to
question, are they the kind

01:00:48.730 --> 01:00:50.100
of people you want
to collaborate?

01:00:50.100 --> 01:00:51.975
Maybe you just consult
them, get their input,

01:00:51.975 --> 01:00:53.639
but you don't actually
work with them.

01:00:53.639 --> 01:00:55.430
But there's a lot of
work to be done there.

01:00:55.430 --> 01:00:58.990
But I that's the big challenge
that leaders have nowadays.

01:00:58.990 --> 01:01:01.490
We have this idea of the
leader as the strong one who

01:01:01.490 --> 01:01:04.610
doesn't change, that can take
the bullets and lead the army

01:01:04.610 --> 01:01:05.110
or whatever.

01:01:05.110 --> 01:01:06.730
The best leaders
are the ones that

01:01:06.730 --> 01:01:09.140
are going to be willing
to change their minds

01:01:09.140 --> 01:01:13.074
and to be humble, basically,
and not say, I'm the greatest

01:01:13.074 --> 01:01:14.740
and I'm always right,
even though that's

01:01:14.740 --> 01:01:17.240
the kind of people that we
tend to think of as leaders,

01:01:17.240 --> 01:01:20.050
because that's who would help
us beat the saber tooth tigers

01:01:20.050 --> 01:01:21.217
or whatever back in the day.

01:01:21.217 --> 01:01:23.258
So, yeah, there's a lot
of work to be done there.

01:01:23.258 --> 01:01:24.740
But I think that's
super important.

01:01:24.740 --> 01:01:26.990
Thank you so much for coming
in and listening to this.

01:01:26.990 --> 01:01:29.550
And if you end up cracking
open the book and reading it,

01:01:29.550 --> 01:01:31.330
go to my website and tell
me what you thought of it.

01:01:31.330 --> 01:01:31.930
Thank you.

01:01:31.930 --> 01:01:35.880
[APPLAUSE]

